\id ISA - Brenton English Septuagint 
\h Isaiah 
\toc1 Isaiah 
\toc2 Isaiah 
\toc3 Is. 
\mt1 ESAIAS 
\c 1 
\p
\v 1 \sc The\sc* vision which Isaiah the son of Amos saw, which he saw against Judah and against Jerusalem, in the reign of Uzziah, and Jotham, and Ahaz, and Hezekiah, who reigned over Judea. 
\p
\v 2 Hear, O heaven, and listen, O earth: for the Lord has spoken, \add saying\add*, I have begotten and reared up children, but they have \f + \fr 1:2 \fqa Or, \ft 'set me at nought.'\f*rebelled against me. 
\v 3 The ox knows his owner, and the ass his master's crib: but Israel does not know me, and the people has not regarded me. 
\p
\v 4 Ah sinful nation, a people full of sins, an evil seed, lawless children: you have forsaken the Lord, and provoked the Holy One of Israel. 
\v 5 Why should you be struck \add any\add* more, transgressing more and more? The whole head is pained, and the whole heart sad. 
\v 6 From the feet to the head, there is no soundness in them; neither wound, nor bruise, nor festering ulcer \add are healed\add*: it isn't possible to apply a plaster, nor oil, nor bandages. 
\v 7 Your land is desolate, your cities burned with fire: strangers devour your land in your presence, and it is made desolate, overthrown by foreign nations. 
\v 8 The daughter of Zion will be deserted like a tent in a vineyard, and like a storehouse of fruits in a garden of cucumbers, like a besieged city. 
\v 9 \x + \xo 1:9 \xt Rom. 9. 29.\x*And if the Lord of Sabaoth had not left us a seed, we should have been like Sodom, and we should have been made like Gomorrah. 
\p
\v 10 Hear the word of the Lord, you rulers of Sodom; pay attention to the law of God, you people of Gomorrah. 
\v 11 The Lord says, Of what \add value\add* to me is the abundance of your sacrifices? I've had enough of whole-burnt-offerings of rams; and I don't delight in the fat of lambs, and the blood of bulls and goats: 
\v 12 don't come \add with these\add* to appear before me; for who has required these things at your hands? You will no more tread my court. 
\v 13 Though you bring fine flour, \add it is\add* vain; incense is an abomination to me; I cannot bear your new moons, and your sabbaths, and the great day; 
\v 14 \add your\add* fasting, and rest from work, your new moons also, and my soul hates your feasts: you have become loathsome to me; I will no more pardon your sins. 
\v 15 When you stretch forth your hands, I will turn away my eyes from you: and though you make many supplications, I will not listen to you; for your hands are full of blood. 
\p
\v 16 Wash yourselves, be clean; remove your wickedness from your souls before my eyes; cease from your wickedness; 
\v 17 learn to do well; diligently seek judgment, deliver the one who is suffering wrong, plead for the orphan, and obtain justice for the widow. 
\p
\v 18 Come, let us reason together, says the Lord: and though your sins be as purple, I will make them white as snow; and though they be as scarlet, I will make \add them\add* white as wool. 
\v 19 If you are willing, and listen to me, you will eat the good of the land: 
\v 20 but if you are unwilling, or won't listen to me, a sword will devour you: for the mouth of the Lord has spoken this. 
\p
\v 21 How has the faithful city Zion, \add once\add* full of judgment, become a prostitute! Righteousness \f + \fr 1:21 \fqa Gr. \ft slept\f*lived there, but now murderers. 
\v 22 Your silver is worthless, your wine merchants mix the wine with water. 
\v 23 Your princes are rebellious, companions of thieves, loving bribes, seeking after rewards; not pleading for orphans, and not heeding the cause of widows. 
\p
\v 24 Therefore thus says the Lord, the Lord of hosts, Woe to the mighty \add men\add* of Israel; for my wrath will not cease against my adversaries, and I will execute judgment on my enemies. 
\v 25 I will bring my hand upon you, and purge you \f + \fr 1:25 \fqa Gr. \ft to pureness.\f*completely, and I will destroy the rebellious, and will take away from you all transgressors. 
\v 26 I will establish your judges as before, and your counsellors as at the beginning: and afterward you will be called the city of righteousness, the faithful mother-city Zion. 
\v 27 For her captives will be saved with judgment, and with mercy. 
\v 28 The transgressors and the sinners will be crushed together, and those who forsake the Lord will be completely consumed. 
\v 29 For they will be ashamed of their idols, which they delighted in, and they are made ashamed of the gardens which they coveted. 
\v 30 For they will be like a terebinth tree that has cast its leaves, and like a garden that has no water. 
\v 31 Their strength will be like a bundle of dry flax, and their works as sparks, and the transgressors and the sinners will be burnt up together, and there will be none to quench \add them\add*. 
\c 2 
\p
\v 1 The word which came to Isaiah the son of Amos concerning Judea, and concerning Jerusalem. 
\p
\v 2 For in the last days the mountain of the Lord will be \f + \fr 2:2 \fqa Or, \ft conspicuous.\f*glorious, and the house of God \add will be\add* on the top of the mountains, and it will be exalted above the hills; and all nations will come to it. 
\v 3 Many nations will go and say, Come, and let us go up to the mountain of the Lord, and to the house of the God of Jacob; and he will tell us his way, and we will walk in it: for out of Zion will go forth the law, and the word of the Lord out of Jerusalem. 
\v 4 He will judge among the nations, and will rebuke many people: and they will beat their swords into plough-shares, and their spears into sickles: and nation will not take up sword against nation, neither will they learn to war any more. 
\p
\v 5 Now, O house of Jacob, come, \add and\add* let us walk in the light of the Lord. 
\v 6 For he has forsaken his people the house of Israel, because their land is filled as at the beginning with divinations, as the \add land\add* of the \f + \fr 2:6 \fqa Or, \ft aliens, see \fqa Appendix \ft which has: “ISAIAH 2. 6. — Philistines. The LXX. generally render by Φιλιστεὶμ or Φυλιστιὶμ till about the middle of Judges, after which the word almost always used is ἀλλόφυλοι. In this there was probably some accommodation of sound to tense.\f*Philistines, and many foreign children were born to them. 
\v 7 For their land is filled with silver and gold, and there was no number of their treasures; their land is also filled with horses, and there was no number of their chariots. 
\v 8 The land is filled with abominations, \add even\add* the works of their hands; and they have worshipped \add the works\add* which their fingers made. 
\v 9 The mean man bowed down, and the great man was humbled: and I will not pardon them. 
\p
\v 10 Now therefore enter into the rocks, and hide yourselves in the earth, for fear of the Lord, and because of the glory of his might, when he arises to terribly strike the earth. 
\v 11 For the eyes of the Lord are high, but man is low; and the haughtiness of men will be brought low, and the Lord alone will be exalted in that day. 
\p
\v 12 For the day of the Lord of hosts will be upon everyone who is proud and haughty, and upon everyone who is high and towering, and they will be brought down; 
\v 13 and upon every cedar of Lebanon, of those who are high and towering, and upon every oak of Basan, 
\v 14 and upon every high mountain, and upon every high hill, 
\v 15 and upon every high tower, and upon every high wall, 
\v 16 and upon every ship of the sea, and upon every display of fine ships. 
\v 17 Every man will be brought low, and the pride of men will fall: and the Lord alone will be exalted in that day. 
\v 18 They will hide all \add idols\add* made with hands, 
\v 19 having carried \add them\add* into the caves, and into the clefts of the rocks, and into the caverns of the earth, for fear of the Lord, and \f + \fr 2:19 \ft See ver 10.\f*because of the glory of his might, when he arises to terribly strike the earth. 
\v 20 For in that day a man will cast forth his silver and gold abominations, which they made \add in order\add* to worship vanities and bats; 
\v 21 to enter into the caverns of the solid rock, and into the clefts of the rocks, for fear of the Lord, and because of the glory of his might, when he arises to terribly strike the earth. 
\c 3 
\p
\v 1 Behold now, the Lord, the Lord of hosts, will take away from Jerusalem and from Judea the mighty man and mighty woman, the strength of bread, and the strength of water, 
\v 2 the great and mighty man, the warrior and the judge, and the prophet, and the counsellor, and the elder, 
\v 3 the captain of fifty also, and the honourable counsellor, and the wise artificer, and the intelligent hearer. 
\v 4 I will make youths their princes, and mockers will rule over them. 
\v 5 The people will fall, man upon man, and \add every\add* man upon his neighbour: the child will insult the elder man, and the base the honourable. 
\v 6 For a man will lay hold of his brother, as one of his father's household, saying, You have clothing, be our ruler, and let my food be under you. 
\v 7 He will answer in that day, and say, I will not be your ruler; for I have no bread in my house, nor clothing: I will not be the ruler of this people. 
\v 8 For Jerusalem is \f + \fr 3:8 \fqa Or, \ft forsaken, \fqa or, \ft let go.\f*ruined, and Judea has fallen, and their tongues \add have spoken\add* with wickedness, disobedient \add as they are\add* towards the Lord. 
\v 9 So now their glory has been brought low, and the shame of their face has withstood them, and they have proclaimed their sin like Sodom, and made it manifest. 
\v 10 Woe to their soul, for they have devised an evil counsel against themselves, saying against themselves, Let us bind the just, for he is burdensome to us: therefore will they eat the fruits of their works. 
\v 11 Woe to the transgressor! Evils will happen to him according to the works of his hands. 
\v 12 O my people, your exactors \f + \fr 3:12 \fqa Gr. \ft glean you.\f*strip you, and extortioners rule over you: O my people, those who pronounce you blessed lead you astray, and pervert the path of your feet. 
\p
\v 13 But now the Lord will stand up for judgment, and will enter into judgment with his people. 
\v 14 The Lord himself will enter into judgment with the elders of the people, and with their rulers: but why have you set my vineyard on fire, and \add why is\add* the spoil of the poor in your houses? 
\v 15 Why do you wrong my people, and shame the face of the poor? 
\p
\v 16 Thus says the Lord, Because the daughters of Zion are haughty, and have walked with an outstretched neck, and with winking of the eyes, and motion of the feet, at the same time drawing their garments in trains, and at the same time mincing with their feet: 
\v 17 therefore the Lord will humble the chief daughters of Zion, and the Lord will expose their form in that day; 
\v 18 and the Lord will take away the glory of their clothing, the curls and the fringes, and the crescents, 
\v 19 and the chains, and the ornaments of their faces, 
\v 20 and the array of glorious ornaments, and the armlets, and the bracelets, and the wreathed work, and the finger-rings, and the ornaments for the right hand, and the ear-rings, 
\v 21 and the garments with scarlet borders, and the garments with purple grounds, 
\v 22 and the shawls to be worn in the house, and the Spartan transparent dresses, 
\v 23 and those made of fine linen, and the purple \add ones\add*, and the scarlet \add ones\add*, and the fine linen, interwoven with gold and purple, and the light coverings for couches. 
\v 24 There will be instead of a sweet smell, dust; and instead of a girdle, you will gird yourself with a rope; and instead of a golden ornament for the head, you will have baldness on account of your works; and instead of a tunic with a scarlet ground, you will gird yourself with sackcloth. 
\v 25 Your most beautiful son whom you love will fall by the sword; and your mighty men will fall by the sword, and will be brought low. 
\v 26 The \f + \fr 3:26 \fqa Gr. \ft cases, \fqa or, \ft repositories.\f*stores of your ornaments will mourn, and you will be left alone, and will be levelled with the ground. 
\c 4 
\p
\v 1 Seven women will take hold of one man, saying, We will eat our own bread, and wear our own clothing: only let your name be called upon us, \add and\add* take away our reproach. 
\p
\v 2 In that day God will shine gloriously in counsel on the earth, to exalt and glorify the remnant of Israel. 
\v 3 It will be, \add that\add* the remnant left in Zion, and the remnant left in Jerusalem, \add even\add* all that are \f + \fr 4:3 \fqa Gr. \ft written for life.\f*appointed to life in Jerusalem, will be called holy. 
\v 4 For the Lord will wash away the filth of the sons and daughters of Zion, and will purge out the blood from their midst, with the spirit of judgment, and the spirit of burning. 
\v 5 He will come, and it will be with regard to every place on mount Zion, yes, a cloud will overshadow all the region round about it by day, and \add there will be\add* as it were the smoke and light of fire burning by night: and over all the glory will be a covering. 
\v 6 It will be for a shadow from the heat, and like a shelter and a hiding-place from inclemency \add of weather\add* and from rain. 
\c 5 
\p
\v 1 Now I will sing to \add my\add* beloved a song of my beloved concerning my vineyard. 
\p \add My\add* beloved had a vineyard on a \f + \fr 5:1 \fqa Gr. \ft horn, so \fqa Heb.\f*high hill in a fertile place. 
\v 2 I made a hedge round it, and fenced it with stakes, and planted a choice vine, and built a tower in the midst of it, and dug a place for the wine-vat in it: and I waited \add for it\add* to bring forth grapes, and it brought forth thorns. 
\v 3 Now, you dwellers in Jerusalem, and \add every\add* man of Judah, judge between me and my vineyard. 
\v 4 What more shall I do to my vineyard that I have not done? For I expected \add it\add* to bring forth grapes, but it has brought forth thorns. 
\v 5 Now I will tell you what I will do to my vineyard: I will take away its hedge, and it will be for a spoil; and I will pull down its walls, and it will be \add left\add* to be trodden down. 
\v 6 I will forsake my vineyard; and it will not be pruned, nor dug, and thorns will come up upon it as on barren land; and I will command the clouds not to rain on it. 
\v 7 For the vineyard of the Lord of hosts is the house of Israel, and \f + \fr 5:7 \fqa Gr. \ft a man.\f*the men of Judah \add his\add* beloved plant: I expected \add it\add* to bring forth judgment, and it brought forth wickedness; and not righteousness, but a cry. 
\p
\v 8 Woe \add to them\add* that join house to house, and add field to field, so they may take away something of their neighbour's: will you dwell alone on the land? 
\v 9 For these things have reached the ears of the Lord of hosts: for though many houses should be built, many and fair houses will be desolate, and there will be no inhabitants in them. 
\v 10 For where ten yoke of oxen plough \add the land\add* will yield one jar-full, and he who sows six homers will produce three measures. 
\p
\v 11 Woe \add to them\add* that rise up in the morning, and follow strong drink; who wait \add at it till\add* the evening: for the wine will inflame them. 
\v 12 For they drink wine with harp, and psaltery, and drums, and pipes: but they don't regard the works of the Lord, and don't consider the works of his hands. 
\p
\v 13 Therefore my people have been taken captive, because they don't know the Lord: and there has been a multitude of dead \add bodies\add*, because of hunger and of thirst for water. 
\v 14 Therefore Hades has enlarged its desire and opened its mouth without ceasing: and her glorious and great, and her rich and her pestilent men will go down \add into it\add*. 
\v 15 The mean man will be brought low, and the great man will be disgraced, and the lofty eyes will be brought low. 
\v 16 But the Lord of hosts will be exalted in judgment, and the holy God will be glorified in righteousness. 
\v 17 Those who were spoiled will be fed like bulls, and lambs will feed on the waste places of those who are taken away. 
\p
\v 18 Woe \add to them\add* who draw sins to them as with a long rope, and wickedness as with a thong of the heifer's yoke: 
\v 19 who say, Let him speedily hasten what he will do, that we may see \add it\add*: and let the counsel of the Holy One of Israel come, that we may know \add it\add*. 
\v 20 Woe \add to them\add* who call evil good, and good evil; who make darkness light, and light darkness; who make bitter sweet, and sweet bitter. 
\v 21 Woe \add to them\add* who are wise in their own conceit, and knowing in their own sight. 
\v 22 Woe to the strong \add ones\add* of you who drink wine, and the mighty \add ones\add* that mingle strong drink: 
\v 23 who justify the ungodly for rewards, and take away the righteousness of the righteous. 
\p
\v 24 Therefore as stubble will be burnt by a coal of fire, and will be consumed by a violent flame, their root will be like chaff, and their flower will go up like dust: for they rejected the law of the Lord of hosts, and insulted the word of the Holy One of Israel. 
\v 25 Therefore the Lord of hosts was greatly angered against his people, and he reached forth his hand upon them, and struck them: and the mountains were troubled, and their carcases were like dung among the way: yet for all this his anger has not been turned away, but his hand is still \f + \fr 5:25 \fqa Gr. \ft High.\f*raised. 
\p
\v 26 Therefore he will lift up a signal to the nations that are afar, and will hiss for them from the end of the earth; and, behold, they are coming very quickly. 
\v 27 They will not hunger nor be weary, neither will they slumber nor sleep; neither will they loose their girdles from their loins, neither will their sandal straps break. 
\v 28 Whose arrows are sharp, and their bows bent; their horses' hoofs are counted as solid rock: their chariot-wheels are like a storm. 
\v 29 They rage like lions, and draw near like a lion's whelps: and he will seize, and roar like a wild beast, and he will cast \add them\add* forth, and there will be none to deliver them. 
\v 30 He will roar on account of them in that day, like the sound of the swelling sea; and they will look to the land, and, behold, \add there will be\add* thick darkness in their perplexity. 
\c 6 
\p
\v 1 It happened in the year in which king Uzziah died, \add that\add* I saw the Lord sitting on a high and exalted throne, and the house was full of his glory. 
\v 2 Seraphs stood around him: each one had six wings: and with two they covered \add their\add* face, and with two they covered \add their\add* feet, and with two they flew. 
\v 3 One cried to the other, and they said, Holy, holy, holy, \add is the\add* Lord of hosts: the whole earth is full of his glory. 
\p
\v 4 The lintel \f + \fr 6:4 \fqa Gr. \ft was lifted.\f*shook at the voice they uttered, and the house was filled with smoke. 
\v 5 I said, Woe is me, for I am pricked to the heart; for being a man, and having unclean lips, I dwell among a people having unclean lips; and I have seen with my eyes the King, the Lord of hosts. 
\v 6 There was sent to me one of the seraphs, and he had in his hand a coal, which he had taken off the altar with the tongs: 
\v 7 and he touched my mouth, and said, Behold, this has touched your lips, and will take away your iniquities, and will purge off your sins. 
\p
\v 8 I heard the voice of the Lord, saying, Whom \f + \fr 6:8 \fqa Or, \ft should I send?\f*will I send, and who will go to this people? And I said, Behold, I am \add here\add*, send me. And he said, Go, and say to this people, 
\v 9 You will hear indeed, but you will not understand; and you will see indeed, but you will not perceive. 
\v 10 \x + \xo 6:10 \xt Mat. 13. 15; Mark 4. 12.\x*For the heart of this people has become dull, and with their ears they hear heavily, and they have closed their eyes; lest they should see with their eyes, and hear with their ears, and understand with their heart, and turn, and I should heal them. 
\v 11 I said, How long, O Lord? And he said, Until the cities are laid waste \f + \fr 6:11 \ft Compare use of παρὰ, \xt Jer. 40. 10,12;\ft also \xt 1 Cor. 12. 15,16.\f*so that they are not inhabited, and the houses so that there are no people, and the land will be left desolate. 
\v 12 After this God will remove the people far off, and those who are left on the land will be multiplied. 
\v 13 Yet there \f + \fr 6:13 \fqa Gr. \ft is.\f*will be a tenth on it, and again it will be for a spoil, like a terebinth tree, and like an acorn when it falls out of its husk. 
\c 7 
\p
\v 1 It happened in the days of Ahaz \add the son\add* of Jotham, the son of Uzziah, king of Judah, there came up Rasin king of Aram, and Phakee son of Romelias, king of Israel, against Jerusalem to war against it, but they could not \f + \fr 7:1 \fqa Lit. \ft besiege See \fqa Heb.\f*take it. 
\v 2 A message was brought to the house of David, saying, Aram has conspired with Ephraim. And the \f + \fr 7:2 \fqa Gr. \ft his\f*king's soul was shaken, and the soul of his people, like a tree in a forest moved by the wind. 
\v 3 The Lord said to Isaiah, Go forth to meet Ahaz, you, and your son Jasub who is left, to the pool of the upper way of the fuller's field. 
\v 4 You will say to him, Take care to be quiet, and don't be afraid; don't let your soul be disheartened because of these two smoking firebrands: for when my fierce anger is over, I will heal again. 
\v 5 And \add as for\add* the son of Aram, and the son of Romelias, because they have devised an evil counsel, \add saying\add*, 
\v 6 We will go up against Judea, and having spoken with them we will turn them to our side, and we will make the son of Tabeel king of it; 
\v 7 thus says the Lord of hosts, This counsel will not abide, nor come to pass. 
\v 8 But the head of Aram is Damascus, and the head of Damascus, Rasim; and yet within sixty and five years the kingdom of Ephraim will cease from \add being\add* a people. 
\v 9 The head of Ephraim is Samaria, and the head of Samaria the son of Romelias: but \f + \fr 7:9 \ft Comp. \fqa Heb.\f*if you don't believe, neither will you at all understand. 
\p
\v 10 The Lord again spoke to Ahaz, saying, 
\v 11 Ask for yourself a sign of the Lord your God, in the depth or in the height. 
\v 12 Ahaz said, I will not ask, neither will I tempt the Lord. 
\v 13 He said, Hear you now, O house of David; is it a little thing for you to contend with men? And how do you contend with the Lord? 
\v 14 Therefore the Lord himself will give you a sign; \x + \xo 7:14 \xt Mat. 1. 23.\x*behold, a virgin will conceive in the womb, and will bring forth a son, and you will call his name Emmanuel. 
\v 15 He will eat butter and honey before he knows to decide on evil, \add or\add* choose the good. 
\v 16 For before the child will know good or evil, he refuses evil, to choose the good; and the land will be forsaken which you are afraid of because of the two kings. 
\p
\v 17 But God will bring upon you, and upon your people, and upon the house of your father, days which have never come, from the day that Ephraim took away from Judah the king of the Assyrians. 
\v 18 It will come to pass in that day that the Lord will hiss for the flies, \f + \fr 7:18 \fqa Or, \ft which part \fqa of the enemy, etc. shall rule over the river of Egypt; but according to \fqa Alex. \ft the reading in the text is the right one.\f*which \add insect\add* will rule over a part of the river of Egypt, and for the bee which is in the land of the Assyrians. 
\v 19 They all will enter into the clefts of the land, and into the holes of the rocks, and into the caves, and into every ravine. 
\v 20 In that day the Lord will shave the head and the hairs of the feet with the hired razor of the king of Assyria beyond the river, and he will remove the beard. 
\v 21 It will come to pass in that day, \add that\add* a man will rear a heifer, and two sheep. 
\v 22 It will come to pass from their \f + \fr 7:22 \fqa Alex. \ft ποιεῖν, 'giving.'\f*drinking an abundance of milk, \add that\add* every one that is left on the land will eat butter and honey. 
\p
\v 23 It will come to pass in that day, \add for\add* every place where there will be a thousand vines at a thousand shekels, they will become \f + \fr 7:23 \fqa Gr. \ft for land and for a thorn.\f*barren land and thorns. 
\v 24 \add Men\add* will enter there with arrow and bow; for all the land will be \add barren\add* ground and thorns. 
\v 25 Every mountain will be certainly ploughed: no fear shall come there: for there will be from \add among\add* the \add barren\add* ground and thorns that whereon cattle will feed and oxen will tread. 
\c 8 
\p
\v 1 The Lord said to me, Take to yourself a large new tablet\f + \fr 8:1 \fqa Alex. \ft paper, \fqa or, \ft parchment.\f*, and write in it with an ordinary pen, Speedily plunder to make spoil; for it is near at hand. 
\v 2 Make me witnesses \add of\add* faithful men, Urias, and Zechariah the son of Barachias. 
\v 3 I went in to the prophetess; and she conceived, and bore a son. And the Lord said to me, Call his name, Spoil quickly, plunder speedily. 
\v 4 For before the child will know \add how\add* to call \add his\add* father or \add his\add* mother, the wealth of Damascus and the spoils of Samaria will be carried off before the king of the Assyrians. 
\p
\v 5 The Lord spoke to me yet again, \add saying\add*, 
\v 6 Because this people doesn't choose the water of Siloam that goes softly, but wills to have Rassin, and the son of Romelias \add to be\add* king over you; 
\v 7 therefore, behold, the Lord brings up on you the water of the river, strong and abundant, \add even\add* the king of the Assyrians, and his glory: and he will come up over all your valleys, and will walk over all your walls: 
\v 8 and he will take away from Judah \add every\add* man who can lift up his head, \add and every one\add* able to accomplish anything; and his camp will fill the breadth of your land, \add O\add* \f + \fr 8:8 \fqa Heb. \ft Immanuel.\f*God with us. 
\p
\v 9 Know, you nations, and be conquered; listen, even to the extremity of the earth: be conquered, after you have strengthened yourselves; for even if you should again strengthen yourselves, you will again be conquered. 
\v 10 Whatever counsel you will take, the Lord will scatter it; and whatever word you will speak, it will not stand among you: for God is with us. 
\v 11 Thus says the Lord, with a strong hand instructing \add me\add* not to walk in the way of this people, saying, 
\v 12 Don't say, \add It is\add* hard, for whatever this people says, is hard: and don't you fear what they fear, neither be dismayed. 
\v 13 Sanctify the Lord himself; and \f + \fr 8:13 \fqa Or, \ft let him be.\f*he will be your fear. 
\v 14 If you will trust in him, he will be a sanctuary to you; and you will not come against \add him\add* as against \x + \xo 8:14 \xt Rom. 9. 33.\x*a stumbling-stone, or as against a rock-fall: but the houses of Jacob are in a snare, and the dwellers in Jerusalem in a pit. 
\v 15 Therefore many among them will be weak, and fall, and be crushed; and they will draw near, and men will be taken securely. 
\v 16 Then those who seal themselves so they may \f + \fr 8:16 \fqa Alex. \ft — 'not.'\f*not learn the law will be made manifest. 
\p
\v 17 And \add one\add* will say, I will wait for God, who has turned away his face from the house of Jacob, and I will trust in him. 
\v 18 \x + \xo 8:18 \xt Heb. 2. 13.\x*Behold I and the children God has given me: and they will be \add for\add* signs and wonders in the house of Israel from the Lord of hosts, who dwells in mount Zion. 
\p
\v 19 If they should say to you, \f + \fr 8:19 \fqa Gr. \ft Seek\f*Consult those who speak from the earth and mediums, those who speak vain words, who speak out of their belly: shouldn't a nation diligently seek their God? Why do they consult the dead concerning the living? 
\v 20 For he has given the law for a help, that they should say, Not like that word for which no payment is given. 
\p
\v 21 Famine will come sorely upon you, and it will come to pass, \add that\add* when you are hungry, you will be grieved, and you will speak ill of the prince and your fathers' ordinances: and they will look up to heaven above, 
\v 22 and they will look on the earth below, and behold severe distress, and darkness, affliction, and \f + \fr 8:22 \fqa Or, \ft a strait.\f*anguish, and darkness so that \add one cannot\add* see; and he who is in anguish will not be distressed only for a time. 
\p
\v 23 Drink this first. \f + \fr 8:23 \fqa Or, \ft do it quickly, \fqa i. e. \ft ‘drink’; See \fqa Hebrew.\f*Act quickly, \x + \xo 8:23 \xt Mat. 4. 15,16.\x*O land of Zebulun, land of Naphtali, and the rest \add inhabiting\add* the sea-coast, and \add the land\add* beyond Jordan, Galilee of the nations. 
\c 9 
\p
\v 1 O people walking in darkness, behold a great light: you who dwell in the region \add and\add* shadow of death, a light will shine upon you. 
\v 2 The \f + \fr 9:2 \fqa Gr. \ft greatest part.\f*multitude of the people who you have brought down in your joy will also rejoice before you as those who rejoice in harvest, and as those who divide the spoil. 
\v 3 Because the yoke that was laid upon them has been taken away, and the rod that was on their neck: for he has broken the rod of those who exact payment, as in the day of Midian. 
\v 4 For every garment gathered together and every cloak acquired will be given up and will be burned as fuel for the fire. 
\p
\v 5 For a child is born to us, and a son is given to us, whose government is upon his shoulder: and his name is called the Messenger of great counsel: \f + \fr 9:5 \fqa Alex. \ft + Wonderful, Counsellor, Mighty One, Potentate, Prince of Peace, Father of the age to come; Compare \xt Heb. 2. 2.\f*for I will bring peace upon the princes, and health to him. 
\v 6 His government will be great, and there is no end to his peace: \add it will be\add* on the throne of David, and \add over\add* his kingdom, to establish it, and to support \add it\add* with judgment and with righteousness, from now on and forever. The zeal of the Lord of hosts will perform this. 
\p
\v 7 The Lord has sent death upon Jacob, and it has come upon Israel. 
\v 8 All the people of Ephraim, and those who dwelt in Samaria will know, who say in their pride and lofty heart, 
\v 9 The bricks have fallen down, but come, let us hew stones, and cut down sycamores and cedars, and let us build for ourselves a tower. 
\v 10 God will dash down those who rise up against him on mount Zion, and will scatter his enemies; 
\v 11 \add even\add* Syria from the rising of the sun, and the Greeks from the setting of the sun, who devour Israel with open mouth. For all this \add his\add* anger isn't turned away, but still \add his\add* hand is raised. 
\p
\v 12 But the people didn't turn until they were struck, and they didn't seek the Lord. 
\v 13 So the Lord took away from Israel the head and tail, great and small, in one day: 
\v 14 the old man, and those who respect persons, this is the head; and the prophet teaching unlawful things, he is the tail. 
\v 15 Those who pronounce this people blessed will mislead them; and they mislead them so they may devour them. 
\v 16 Therefore the Lord will not take pleasure in their young men, neither he will have pity on their orphans or on their widows: for they are all transgressors and wicked, and every mouth speaks unjustly. For all this \add his\add* anger isn't turned away, but \add his\add* hand is still raised. 
\p
\v 17 Wickedness will burn like fire, and will be devoured by fire like dry grass: and it will burn in the thickets of the wood, and will devour all that is round about the hills. 
\v 18 The whole earth is set on fire because of the fierce anger of the Lord, and the people will be like men burnt by fire: no man will pity his brother. 
\v 19 But \add one\add* will turn aside to the right hand, for he will be hungry; and will eat on the left, yet he will not be satisfied; each will eat the flesh of his own arm. 
\v 20 For Manasseh will eat \add the flesh\add* of Ephraim, and Ephraim \add the flesh\add* of Manasseh; for they will besiege Judah together. For all this \add his\add* anger isn't turned away, but \add his\add* hand is still raised. 
\c 10 
\p
\v 1 Woe to those who write wickedness; for when they write, they write wickedness, 
\v 2 perverting the cause of the poor, violently wresting the judgment of the needy of my people, that the widow may be prey to them, and the orphan may be spoil. 
\v 3 What will they do in the day of visitation? For affliction will come to you from afar: and to whom will you flee for help? And where will you leave your glory, 
\v 4 that you may not fall into \f + \fr 10:4 \fqa Heb. \ft and \fqa Alex. \ft + ‘and they shall fall under the slain’.\f*captivity? 
\p For all this \add his\add* wrath isn't turned away, but \add his\add* hand is still raised. 
\p
\v 5 Woe to the Assyrians; the rod of my wrath and anger is in their hands. 
\v 6 I will send my wrath against a sinful nation, and I will charge my people to take plunder and spoil, and to trample the cities, and to make them dust. 
\v 7 But he did not think so, and in his soul it is not reckoned so: but his mind will turn to destroying many nations. 
\v 8 If they should say to him, You alone are ruler; 
\v 9 then will he say, Have I not taken the country above Babylon and Chalanes, where the tower was built? And have I \add not\add* taken Arabia, and Damascus, and Samaria? 
\v 10 As I have taken them, I will also take all the kingdoms. Howl, you idols in Jerusalem, and in Samaria. 
\v 11 For as I did to Samaria and her idols, so will I do also to Jerusalem and her idols. 
\v 12 It will come to pass, when the Lord has finished doing everything on Mount Zion and Jerusalem, \add that\add* I will punish the \f + \fr 10:12 \fqa Gr. \ft great mind.\f*proud heart, \add even\add* the ruler of the Assyrians, and the boastful haughtiness of his eyes. 
\v 13 For he said, I will act in strength, and in the wisdom of \add my\add* understanding I will remove the boundaries of nations, and will spoil their strength. 
\v 14 I will shake the inhabited cities: and I will take with my hand all the world like a nest: and I will take them like eggs that have been left; and there is no one who will escape me, or contradict me. 
\v 15 Will the axe glorify itself without the one who chops with it? Or will the saw lift up itself without the one who uses it, as if one should lift a rod or staff? But it will not be so; 
\v 16 but the Lord of hosts will send dishonour upon your honour, and burning fire will be kindled upon your glory. 
\v 17 The light of Israel will be for a fire, and he will sanctify him with burning fire, and it will devour the wood like grass. 
\v 18 In that day the mountains will be consumed, and the hills, and the forests, and \add fire\add* will devour \add both\add* soul and body: and he who flees will be like one fleeing from burning flame. 
\v 19 Those who are left will be a \add small\add* number, and a child will write them. 
\p
\v 20 It will come to pass in that day \add that\add* the remnant of Israel will no more \f + \fr 10:20 \fqa Or, \ft repeat their offence.\f*join themselves with those who injured them, and the saved of Jacob will no more trust in them; but they will truly trust in the Holy God of Israel. 
\v 21 The remnant of Jacob will \add trust\add* in the mighty God. 
\v 22 \x + \xo 10:22 \xt Rom. 9. 27,28.\x*And even if the people of Israel are like the sand of the sea, only a remnant of them will be saved; 
\v 23 for he is bringing a word to completion, and cutting it short in righteousness: because the Lord will carry out a shortened word in all the world. 
\p
\v 24 Therefore thus says the Lord of hosts, Don't be afraid of the Assyrians, my people who dwell in Zion, because he will strike you with a rod: for I am bringing a stroke upon you, to see the way of Egypt. 
\v 25 For in a little while the indignation will cease: but my wrath will be against their \f + \fr 10:25 \fqa sc. \ft of their enemies.\f*council. 
\v 26 God will stir up \add enemies\add* against them, according to the stroke of Midian in the place of affliction: and his wrath will be by the way of the sea, \add even\add* to the way that leads to Egypt. 
\v 27 It will come to pass in that day, \add that\add* his yoke will be taken away from your shoulder, and your fear of him, and the yoke will be destroyed from off your shoulders. 
\p
\v 28 For he will arrive at the city of Angai, and will pass on to Maggedo, and will lay up his stores in Machmas. 
\v 29 He will pass by the valley, and will arrive at Angai: fear will seize upon Rama, the city of Saul. 
\v 30 The daughter of Gallim will flee; Laisa will hear; one will hear in Anathoth. 
\v 31 Madebena also is amazed, and the inhabitants of Gibbir. 
\p
\v 32 Today, on the way to remain, he gestures with his hand to the mountain, the daughter of Zion, and the hills of Jerusalem. 
\p
\v 33 Behold, the Lord, the Lord of hosts, will mightily confound the glorious ones; and the haughty in pride will be crushed, and the lofty will be brought low: 
\v 34 and the lofty ones will fall by the sword, and Lebanon will fall with his lofty ones. 
\c 11 
\p
\v 1 \x + \xo 11:1 \xt Rom. 15. 12.\x*A rod will come forth out of the root of Jesse, and a blossom will come up from \add his\add* root: 
\v 2 and the Spirit of God will rest upon him, the spirit of wisdom and understanding, the spirit of counsel and strength, the spirit of knowledge and godliness will fill him; 
\v 3 the spirit of the fear of God. He will not judge according to appearance, nor reprove according to report: 
\v 4 but he will judge the cause of the lowly, and will reprove the lowly of the earth: and he will strike the earth with the word of his mouth, and with the breath of his lips he will destroy the ungodly one. 
\v 5 He will have his loins girt with righteousness, and his sides clothed with truth. 
\p
\v 6 The wolf will feed with the lamb, and the leopard will lie down with the kid; and the young calf and bull and lion will feed together; and a little child will lead them. 
\v 7 The ox and bear will feed together; and their young will be together: and the lion will eat straw like the ox. 
\v 8 An infant will put his hand on the holes of asps, and on the nest of young asps. 
\v 9 They will not hurt, nor will they at all be able to destroy any one on my holy mountain: for the whole \add world\add* is filled with the knowledge of the Lord, as much water \f + \fr 11:9 \fqa Gr. \ft may cover.\f*covers the seas. 
\v 10 In that day \x + \xo 11:10 \xt Rom. 15. 12.\x*there will be a root of Jesse, and he who will arise to rule over the nations; the nations will trust in him and his rest will be glorious. 
\v 11 It will be in that day, \add that\add* the Lord will again show his hand, to be zealous for the remnant of the people who are left, who will be left by the Assyrians, and from Egypt, and from the country of Babylon, and from Ethiopia, and from the Elamites, and from the rising of the sun, and out of Arabia. 
\v 12 He will lift up a standard for the nations, and he will gather the lost of Israel, and he will gather the dispersed of Judah from the four corners of the earth. 
\v 13 The envy of Ephraim will be taken away, and the enemies of Judah will perish: Ephraim will not envy Judah, and Judah will not afflict Ephraim. 
\v 14 They will fly in the ships of the Philistines: they will at the same time spoil the \f + \fr 11:14 \fqa sc. \ft the west.\f*sea, and those \add who come\add* from the east, and Idumea: and they will lay their hands on Moab first; but the children of Ammon will first obey \add them\add*. 
\p
\v 15 The Lord will make desolate the sea of Egypt; and he will lay his hand on the river with a strong wind, and he will \f + \fr 11:15 \fqa q. d. \ft form by smiting.\f*strike the seven channels, so that men will pass through it dry-shod. 
\v 16 There will be a passage for my people left in Egypt: and it will be to Israel as the day when he came forth out of the land of Egypt. 
\c 12 
\p
\v 1 In that day you will say, I \add will\add* bless you, O Lord; for you were angry with me, but you have turned aside your wrath, and have pitied me. 
\v 2 Behold, my God is my Saviour; I will trust in him, and not be afraid: for the Lord is my glory and my praise, and he has become my salvation. 
\v 3 Therefore draw water with joy out of the wells of salvation. 
\v 4 In that day you will say, Sing to the Lord, call aloud on his name, proclaim his glorious \add deeds\add* among the nations; make mention that his name is exalted. 
\v 5 Sing praise to the name of the Lord; for he has done great \add things\add*: declare this in all the earth. 
\v 6 Exalt and rejoice, you who dwell in Zion: for the Holy One of Israel is exalted in your midst. 
\c 13 
\d
\v 1 \sc The Vision which Isaiah son of Amos saw against Babylon.\sc* 
\p
\v 2 Lift up a standard on the mountain of the plain, exalt the voice to them, beckon with the hand, open \add the gates\add*, you rulers. 
\v 3 I give command, and I bring them: giants are coming to fulfil my wrath, rejoicing at the same time and insulting. 
\v 4 A voice of many nations on the mountains, \add even\add* like \add to that\add* of many nations; a voice of kings and nations gathered together: the Lord of hosts has given command to \f + \fr 13:4 \fqa Lit. \ft fighting with armour or weapons.\f*a war-like nation, 
\v 5 to come from a land afar off, from the utmost foundation of heaven; the Lord and his warriors \add are coming\add* to destroy all the world. 
\p
\v 6 Howl for the day of the Lord is near, and destruction from God will arrive. 
\v 7 Therefore every hand will become powerless, and every soul of man will be dismayed. 
\v 8 The elders will be troubled, and pangs will seize them, like of a woman in labor: and they will mourn one to another, and will be amazed, and will change their face like a flame. 
\v 9 For behold! The day of the Lord is coming which cannot be \f + \fr 13:9 \fqa Gr. \ft healed.\f*escaped, \add a day\add* of wrath and anger, to make the world desolate, and to destroy sinners out of it. 
\v 10 For the stars of heaven, and Orion, and all the host of heaven, will not give their light; and it will be dark at sunrise, and the moon will not give her light. 
\v 11 I will command evils for the whole world, and \add will visit\add* their sins on the ungodly: and I will destroy the pride of transgressors, and will bring low the pride of the haughty. 
\v 12 Those who are left will be more precious than gold tried in the fire; and a man will be more precious than the stone that is in Suphir. 
\v 13 For the heaven will be enraged, and the earth will be shaken from her foundation, because of the fierce anger of the Lord of hosts, in the day in which his wrath will come on. 
\v 14 Those who are left will be like a fleeing fawn, and like a stray sheep, and there will be none to gather \add them\add*: so that a man will turn back to his people, and a man will flee to his own land. 
\v 15 For whoever will be taken will be overcome; and those who are gathered together will fall by the sword. 
\v 16 They will dash their children before their eyes; and they will spoil their houses, and will take their wives. 
\p
\v 17 Behold, I will stir up against you the Medes, who do not regard silver, neither have they need of gold. 
\v 18 They will break the bows of the young men; and they will have no mercy on your children; nor will their eyes spare your children. 
\v 19 Babylon, which is called glorious by the king of the Chaldeans, will be like \add when\add* God overthrew Sodom and Gomorrah. 
\v 20 It will never be inhabited, neither will any enter into it for many generations: neither will the Arabs pass through it; nor will shepherds rest in it. 
\v 21 But wild beasts will rest there; and the houses will be filled with howling; and \f + \fr 13:21 \ft See \xt Job 30. 29; Is. 34. 13, \ft etc. Sirens in the Greek are mythic creatures associated with desolate places and eerie calls. It's the same word as in the older story from Homer where Odysseus has his crew plug their ears with wax and tie him to the mast so he can hear the sirens’ song without steering the ship onto the rocks, but by the time the LXX was translated its meaning had broadened and here it is not about their role as temptresses but as strange, haunting beings of desolation. (Brenton translates this as 'monsters', but the word is more specific than that.)\f*sirens will rest there, and demons will dance there, 
\v 22 and \f + \fr 34:14 \ft 'Onocentaurs' is a transliteration of the Greek ὀνοκένταυροι where the ono- part means donkey. Brenton has 'satyrs' here and while that has the right feel of monstrous hybrids, the image it summons is rather different to that of the Greek.\f*onocentaurs will dwell there; and \f + \fr 13:22 \ft The precise animal is uncertain. The Greek ἐχῖνος probably refers to a hedgehog-like desert animal.\f*hedgehogs will make their nests in their houses. \f + \fr 13:22 \ft See \xt Heb. 10. 37; Hab. 2. 3.\f*It will come soon, and will not tarry. 
\c 14 
\p
\v 1 The Lord will have mercy on Jacob, and will yet choose Israel, and they will rest on their land: and the stranger will be added to them, yes, will be added to the house of Jacob. 
\v 2 The nations will take them, and bring them into their place: and they will \f + \fr 14:2 \fqa i. e. \ft the Israelites.\f*inherit them, and \f + \fr 14:2 \fqa i. e. \ft the Gentiles.\f*they will be multiplied upon the land for servants and handmaidens: and those who took them captives will become captives \add to them\add*; and those who had lordship over them will be under \add their\add* rule. 
\p
\v 3 It will come to pass in that day, \add that\add* the Lord will give you rest from your sorrow and vexation, \add and from\add* your hard servitude with which you served them. 
\v 4 You will take up this lamentation against the king of Babylon, 
\p \f + \fr 14:4 \fqa Alex. \ft + 'and thou shalt say in that day'.\f*How has the extortioner ceased, and the taskmaster ceased! 
\v 5 The Lord has broken the yoke of sinners, the yoke of princes. 
\v 6 Having struck a nation in wrath, with an incurable plague, striking a nation with a wrathful plague, which didn't spare \add them\add*, he rested in quiet. 
\v 7 All the earth cries aloud with joy: 
\v 8 the trees of Lebanon also rejoice against you, and the cedar of Lebanon, \add saying\add*, From the time that you have been laid low, no one has come up to cut us down. 
\v 9 Hades from beneath is provoked to meet you: all the great ones that have ruled over the earth have risen up together against you, those who have raised up from their thrones all the kings of the nations. 
\v 10 All will answer and say to you, You also have been taken, even as we were; and you are numbered amongst us. 
\v 11 Your glory has come down to Hades, and your great mirth: under you they will spread corruption, and the worm will be your covering. 
\v 12 How has the morning star, that rose in the morning, fallen from heaven! He who sent \add orders\add* to all the nations is crushed to the earth. 
\v 13 But you said in your heart, I will go up to heaven, I will set my throne above the stars of heaven: I will sit on a lofty mount, on the lofty mountains toward the north: 
\v 14 I will go up above the clouds; I will be like the Most High. 
\v 15 But now you will go down to Hades, even to the foundations of the earth. 
\v 16 Those who see you will wonder at you, and say, \f + \fr 14:16 \ft See chap \xt 5. 25.\f*This is the man who troubled the earth, who made kings shake; 
\v 17 who made the whole world desolate, and destroyed its cities; he didn't release those who were in captivity. 
\v 18 All the kings of the nations lie in honour, \add every\add* man in his house. 
\v 19 But you will be cast forth on the mountains, like a loathed carcase, with many dead who have been pierced with swords, going down to the grave. 
\v 20 As a garment defiled with blood will not be pure, so neither will you be pure; because you have destroyed my land, and have killed my people: you will not endure forever, you evil seed. 
\v 21 Prepare your children to be killed for the sins of their father; that they don't arise, and inherit the earth, nor fill the earth with wars. 
\v 22 I will rise up against them, says the Lord of hosts, and I will destroy their name, and remnant, and seed: thus says the Lord. 
\v 23 I will make the region of Babylon desert, so that hedgehogs will dwell \add there\add*, and it will come to nothing: and I will make it a pit of clay for destruction. 
\p
\v 24 Thus says the Lord of hosts, As I have said, so it will be: and as I have purposed, so \add the matter\add* will remain: 
\v 25 \add even\add* to destroy the Assyrians upon my land, and upon my mountains: and they will be for trampling; and their yoke will be taken away from them, and their glory will be taken away from their shoulders. 
\v 26 This is the purpose which the Lord has purposed upon the whole earth: and this is the hand that is lifted up against all the nations. 
\v 27 For what the Holy God has purposed, who will frustrate? And who will turn back his uplifted hand? 
\p
\v 28 In the year in which king Ahaz died this word came. 
\p
\v 29 Don't rejoice, all you foreigners, because the yoke of him who struck you is broken: for out of the seed of the snake will come forth the young of asps, and their young will come forth as flying snakes. 
\v 30 The poor will be fed by him, and poor men will rest in peace: but he will destroy your seed with hunger, and will destroy your remnant. 
\v 31 Howl, you gates of cities; let the cities be troubled and cry, \add even\add* all the foreigns: for smoke is coming from the north, and there is no \add possibility\add* \f + \fr 14:31 \fqa Gr. \ft of being.\f*of living. 
\v 32 What will the kings of the nations answer? That the Lord has founded Zion, and by him the poor of the people will be saved. 
\c 15 
\d
\v 1 \sc The Word against the Land of Moab.\sc* 
\p By night the land of Moab will be destroyed; for by night the wall of the land of Moab will be destroyed. 
\v 2 Grieve for yourselves; for even Debon, where your altar is, will be destroyed: there you will go up to weep, over Nabau of the land of Moab: howl you: baldness will be on every head, \add and\add* all arms \add will be\add* \f + \fr 15:2 \fqa Gr. \ft cut to pieces.\f*wounded. 
\v 3 Gird yourselves with sackcloth in her streets: and lament upon her roofs, and in her streets, and in her ways; howl all of you with weeping. 
\v 4 For Esebon and Eleale have cried: their voice was heard to Jassa: therefore the loins of the region of Moab cry aloud; her soul will know. 
\v 5 The heart of the region of Moab cries within her to Segor; for it is \add as\add* a heifer of three years old: and on the ascent of Luith they will go up to you weeping by the way of Aroniim: she cries, Destruction, and trembling. 
\v 6 The water of Nemerim will be desolate, and its grass will fail: for there will be no green grass. 
\v 7 Will \add Moab\add* still be delivered? For I \add will\add* bring the Arabs upon the valley, and they will take it. 
\v 8 For the cry has reached the border of the region of Moab, \add even\add* of Agalim; and her howling \add has gone\add* as far as the well of Ælim. 
\v 9 The water of Remmon will be filled with blood: for I will bring Arabs upon Remmon, and I will take away the seed of Moab, and Ariel, and the remnant of Adama. 
\c 16 
\p
\v 1 I will send \f + \fr 16:1 \ft The Greek does not specify what is sent; the phrase ‘like creeping things’ stands without an explicit object.\f*like creeping things on the land: is Mount Zion a desolate rock? 
\v 2 For you will be like a flying bird, like a chick snatched away, daughter of Moab: and then you, O Arnon, 
\v 3 take farther counsel, and continually make you a shelter from grief: they flee in darkness at midday; they are amazed; don't be led captive. 
\v 4 The fugitives of Moab will sojourn with you; they will be to you a shelter from the face of the pursuer: for your alliance has been taken away, and the oppressing ruler has perished from off the earth. 
\v 5 A throne will be established with mercy; and one will sit upon it with truth in the tent of David, judging, and earnestly seeking judgments, and hurrying righteousness. 
\p
\v 6 We have heard of the arrogance of Moab; very arrogant indeed. You have lifted up your pride. Not so is your oracle. 
\p
\v 7 Moab will howl; for all will howl in the land of Moab: but you will care for those who dwell in Seth, and you will not be ashamed. 
\v 8 The plains of Esebon will mourn, the vine of Sebama: swallowing up the nations. Trample her vines, even to Jazer: you will not come together; wander in the desert. Those who were sent are deserted, for they have gone over to the sea. 
\v 9 Therefore I will weep as with the weeping of Jazer for the vine of Sebama; Esebon and Eleale have cast down your trees; for I will trample on your harvest and on your vintages, and all \add your plants\add* will fall. 
\v 10 Gladness and rejoicing will be taken away from the vineyards; and they will not rejoice at all in your vineyards; and they will not at all tread wine into the vats; for \add the vintage\add* has ceased. 
\v 11 Therefore my belly will sound like a harp for Moab, and \f + \fr 16:11 \ft Compare the Hebrew. The Greek may represent a misread place name.\f*my inward parts as a wall you have repaired. 
\v 12 It will be to your shame, (for Moab is wearied at the altars,) that he will go in to its idols to pray, but they will not all able to deliver him at all. 
\p
\v 13 This is the word which the Lord spoke against Moab, when he spoke. 
\v 14 Now I say, In three years, of the years of a hireling, the glory of Moab will be dishonoured \add with\add* all his great wealth; and he will be left few in number, and not honoured. 
\c 17 
\d
\v 1 \sc The Word against Damascus.\sc* 
\p Behold, Damascus will be taken away from among cities, and will become a ruin; 
\v 2 abandoned forever, to \add be\add* a fold and resting-place for flocks, and there will be no one to go after them. 
\v 3 She will no longer be a strong place for Ephraim to flee to, and there will no longer be a kingdom in Damascus, or a remnant of Syrians; for you are no better than the children of Israel, \add even\add* than their glory; thus says the Lord of hosts. 
\v 4 There will be in that day a failure of the glory of Jacob, and the riches of his glory will be shaken. 
\v 5 It will be as if one should gather standing grain, and reap the grain of the ears; and it will be as if one should gather ears of grain in a rich valley; 
\v 6 and \add as if\add* there should be stubble left there, or \add as it were\add* the berries of an olive tree, two or three on the topmost bough, or \add as if\add* four or five should be left on their branches; thus says the Lord, the God of Israel. 
\p
\v 7 In that day a man will trust in the one who made him, and his eyes will have respect to the Holy One of Israel. 
\v 8 They will not trust in their altars at all, nor in the works of their hands which their fingers made; and they will not look to the trees, nor to their abominations. 
\p
\v 9 In that day your cities will be deserted, as the Amorites and the Evæans deserted \add theirs\add*, because of the children of Israel; and they will be desolate. 
\v 10 Because you have forsaken God your Saviour, and have not been mindful of the Lord your helper; therefore you will plant a \f + \fr 17:10 \fqa Gr. \ft faithless.\f*false plant, and a false seed. 
\v 11 In the day when you plant you will be deceived; but if you sow in the morning, \add the seed\add* will spring up for a crop in the day in which you obtain an inheritance, and as a man's father, you will obtain an inheritance for your sons. 
\p
\v 12 Woe \add to\add* the multitude of many nations, like the swelling sea, so you will be greatly agitated; and the \f + \fr 17:12 \fqa Gr. \ft back; Complut. reads ἠχος, ‘noise’.\f*force of many nations will sound like water; 
\v 13 many nations like much water, as when much water rushes violently: and they will drive him away, and pursue him afar, like the dust of chaff when men winnow before the wind, and like a storm whirling the dust of the wheel. 
\p
\v 14 Toward evening there will be grief; before the morning, it is no more. This is the portion of those who spoiled you, and the inheritance to those who took you as their inheritance. 
\c 18 
\p
\v 1 Woe to you, you wings of the land of ships, beyond the rivers of Ethiopia. 
\v 2 \f + \fr 18:2 \fqa Gr. \ft He that sends.\f*He sends messengers by the sea, and papyrus boats on the water: for swift messengers will go to a lofty nation, and to a foreign and harsh people. Who is beyond it? A nation not looked for, and trodden down. 
\v 3 Now all the rivers of the land will be inhabited as an inhabited country; their land will be as when a signal is raised from a mountain; it will be audible as the sound of a trumpet. 
\v 4 For thus said the Lord to me, There will be security in my city, as the light of noonday heat, and it will be like a cloud of dew in the day of harvest. 
\v 5 Before the reaping time, when the flower has been completely formed, and the unripe grape has put forth its flower and blossomed, then will he take away the little clusters with pruning-hooks, and will take away the small branches, and cut them off; 
\v 6 and he will leave \add them\add* together to the birds of the sky, and to the wild beasts of the earth: and the fowls of the sky will be gathered upon them, and all the beasts of the land will come upon him. 
\v 7 In that time presents will be brought to the Lord of hosts from a people afflicted and harried, and from a people great from now on and forever; a nation hoping and \add yet\add* trodden down, which is in a part of a river of his land, to the place where the name of the Lord of hosts is invoked: Mount Zion. 
\c 19 
\d
\v 1 \sc The Vision of Egypt.\sc* 
\p Behold, the Lord sits on a swift cloud, and will come to Egypt: and the idols of Egypt will be moved at his presence, and their heart will faint within them. 
\v 2 The Egyptians will be stirred up against the Egyptians: and a man will fight against his brother, and a man against his neighbour, city against city, and \f + \fr 19:2 \fqa Alex. \ft ‘district,’ the accent being different.\f*law against \f + \fr 19:2 \fqa Alex. \ft ‘district,’ the accent being different.\f*law. 
\v 3 The spirit of the Egyptians will be troubled within them; and I will frustrate their counsel: and they will enquire of their gods and their images, and \f + \fr 19:3 \fqa Gr. \ft the ventriloquists.\f*those who speak out of the earth, and those who have in them a divining spirit. 
\v 4 I will deliver Egypt into the hands of men, of cruel lords; and cruel kings will rule over them: thus says the Lord of hosts. 
\v 5 The Egyptians will drink the water that is by the sea, but the river will fail, and be dried up. 
\v 6 The streams will fail, and the canals of the river; and every \f + \fr 19:6 \fqa Lit. \ft gathering; See \xt Gen. 1. 9. \ft also \xt Jer. 28. 32.\f*reservoir of water will be dried up, in every marsh also of reed and papyrus. 
\v 7 All the green herbage around the river, and everything sown by the side of the river, will be blasted with the wind and dried up. 
\v 8 The fishermen will groan, and all who cast a hook into the river will groan; they also who cast nets, and the anglers will mourn. 
\v 9 Shame will come upon those who work fine flax, and those who \f + \fr 19:9 \fqa Gr. \ft work at.\f*make fine linen. 
\v 10 Those who work at them will be in pain, and all who make beer will be grieved, and be pained in their souls. 
\v 11 The princes of Tanis will be fools: \add as for\add* the king's wise counsellors, their counsel will be turned into folly: how will you say to the king, We are sons of wise men, sons of ancient kings? 
\v 12 Where are now your wise men? And let them declare to you, and say, What has the Lord of hosts purposed upon Egypt? 
\v 13 The princes of Tanis have failed, and the princes of Memphis are lifted up \add with pride\add*, and they will cause Egypt to wander by tribes. 
\v 14 For the Lord has prepared for them a spirit of error, and they have caused Egypt to err in all their works, like one who is drunk staggers and also vomits. 
\v 15 There will be no work for the Egyptians which will accomplish head or tail, beginning or end. 
\p
\v 16 But in that day the Egyptians will be like women, in fear and in trembling because of the hand of the Lord of hosts, which he will bring upon them. 
\v 17 The land of the Jews will be for a terror to the Egyptians: whoever will name it to them, they will fear, because of the counsel which the Lord of hosts has purposed concerning it. 
\v 18 In that day there will be five cities in Egypt speaking the language of Canaan, and swearing by the name of the Lord of hosts; one city will be called the \f + \fr 19:18 \fqa Heb. \ft city of destruction.\f*city of Asedec. 
\v 19 In that day there will be an altar to the Lord in the land of the Egyptians, and a pillar to the Lord by its border. 
\v 20 It will be for a sign to the Lord forever in the land of Egypt: for they will presently cry to the Lord because of those who afflict them, and he will send them a man who will save them; he will judge and save them. 
\v 21 The Lord will be known to the Egyptians, and the Egyptians will know the Lord in that day; and they will offer sacrifices, and will vow vows to the Lord, and pay \add them\add*. 
\v 22 The Lord will strike the Egyptians with a great blow, and he will completely heal them: and they will return to the Lord, and he will hear them, and thoroughly heal them. 
\v 23 In that day there will be a way from Egypt to the Assyrians, and the Assyrians will enter into Egypt, and the Egyptians will go to the Assyrians, and the Egyptians will serve the Assyrians. 
\v 24 In that day Israel will be third with the Egyptians and the Assyrians, blessed in the land which the Lord of hosts has blessed, 
\v 25 saying, Blessed be my people who are in Egypt, and who are among the Assyrians, and Israel my inheritance. 
\c 20 
\p
\v 1 In the year when Tanathan came to Azotus, when he was sent by Arna king of the Assyrians, and warred against Azotus, and took it; 
\v 2 then the Lord spoke to Isaiah the son of Amos, saying, Go and take the sackcloth off your loins, and take your sandals off your feet, and do thus, going naked and barefoot. 
\v 3 The Lord said, As my servant Isaiah has walked naked and barefoot three years, there will be three years for signs and wonders to the Egyptians and Ethiopians; 
\v 4 for thus will the king of the Assyrians lead the captivity of Egypt and the Ethiopians, young men and old, naked and barefoot, having the shame of Egypt exposed. 
\v 5 The Egyptians being defeated will be ashamed of the Ethiopians, in whom they had trusted; for they were their glory. 
\v 6 Those who dwell in this coastland will say in that day, Behold, we trusted to flee to them for help, who could not save themselves from the king of the Assyrians: and how will we be saved? 
\c 21 
\d
\v 1 \sc The Vision of the Desert.\sc* 
\p As though a whirlwind should pass through the desert, coming from a desert, \add even\add* from such a land, 
\v 2 \add so\add* a fearful and a grievous vision was declared to me: he who is treacherous deals treacherously, the transgressor transgresses. The Elamites are upon me, and the ambassadors of the Persians come against me: now will I groan and comfort myself. 
\v 3 Therefore my loins are filled with feebleness, and pangs have seized me like a woman in labor: I dealt wrongfully that I might not hear; I hastened that I might not see. 
\v 4 My heart wanders, and transgression \f + \fr 21:4 \fqa Lit. \ft baptizes.\f*overwhelms me; my soul is occupied with fear. 
\v 5 Prepare the table, eat, drink: arise, you princes, and prepare \add your\add* shields. 
\v 6 For thus said the Lord to me, Go and station a watchman for yourself, and declare whatever you will see. 
\v 7 I saw two mounted horsemen, and a rider on an ass, and a rider on a camel. 
\v 8 Listen with great attention, and call Urias to the watch-tower: the Lord has spoken. I stood continually during the day, and I stood in the camp all the night: 
\v 9 and, behold, he comes riding in a chariot and pair: and he answered and said, Babylon is fallen, is fallen; and all her images and her idols have been crushed to the ground. 
\v 10 Hear, you who are left, and you who are in pain, hear what things I have heard of the Lord of hosts \add which\add* the God of Israel has declared to us. 
\d
\v 11 \sc The Vision of Idumea.\sc* 
\p Call to me out of Seir; guard the bulwarks. 
\v 12 I watch in the morning and the night: if you would enquire, enquire, and dwell by me. 
\v 13 You may lodge in the forest \f + \fr 21:13 \fqa Heb. \ft of Arabia.\f*in the evening, or in the way of Dædan. 
\p
\v 14 You who dwell in the country of Thæman, bring water to meet him who is thirsty; 
\v 15 meet the fugitives with bread, because of the multitude of the killed, and because of the multitude of those who lose their way, and because of the multitude of swords, and because of the multitude of bent bows, and because of the multitude of those who have fallen in war. 
\v 16 For thus said the Lord to me, Yet a year, as the year of a hireling, \add and\add* the glory of the sons of Kedar will fail: 
\v 17 and the remnant of the strong bows of the sons of Kedar will be small: for the Lord God of Israel has spoken \add it\add*. 
\c 22 
\d
\v 1 \sc The Word of the Valley of Zion.\sc* 
\p What has happened to you, that now you are all gone up to the housetops in vain? 
\v 2 The city is filled with shouting \add men\add*: your killed are not killed with swords, nor are your dead those who have died in battle. 
\v 3 All your princes have fled, and \add your\add* captives are tightly bound, and the mighty \add men\add* in you have fled far away. 
\v 4 Therefore I said, Let me alone, I will weep bitterly; don't labour to comfort me for the breach of the daughter of my people. 
\v 5 For \add it is\add* a day of trouble, and of destruction, and of treading down, and \add there is\add* perplexity \add sent\add* from the Lord of hosts: they wander in the valley of Zion; they wander from the least to the greatest on the mountains. 
\v 6 The Elamites took \add their\add* quivers, and \add there were\add* men mounted on horses, and \add there was\add* a gathering for battle. 
\v 7 It will be \add that\add* your choice valleys will be filled with chariots, and horsemen will block up your gates. 
\v 8 They will uncover the gates of Judah, and they will look in that day on the choice houses of the city. 
\v 9 They will uncover the secret places of the houses of the citadel of David: and they saw that they were many, and that one \add had\add* turned the water of the old pool into the city; 
\v 10 and that they \add had\add* pulled down the houses of Jerusalem, to fortify the wall of the city. 
\v 11 You procured to yourselves water between the two walls within the ancient pool: but you didn't look to him who made it from the beginning, and didn't regard him that created it. 
\v 12 The Lord, the Lord of hosts, called in that day for weeping, and lamentation, and \f + \fr 22:12 \fqa Gr. \ft shaving.\f*baldness, and for girding with sackcloth: 
\v 13 but they engaged in joy and gladness, killing calves, and killing sheep, so as to eat meat, and drink wine; saying, Let us eat and drink; for to-morrow we die. 
\v 14 These things are revealed in the ears of the Lord of hosts: for this sin will not be forgiven you, until you die. 
\p
\v 15 Thus says the Lord of hosts, Go into the chamber, to Somnas the \f + \fr 22:15 \fqa Or, \ft steward.\f*treasurer, and say to him, Why are you here? 
\v 16 and what do you have to do here, that you have here hewn yourself a sepulchre, and made yourself a sepulchre on high, and have graven for yourself a dwelling in the rock? 
\v 17 Behold now, the Lord of hosts casts forth and will completely destroy \add such\add* a man, and will take away your robe and your glorious crown, 
\v 18 and will cast you into a great and unmeasured land, and there you will die: and he will bring your fair chariot to shame, and the house of your prince to be trodden down. 
\v 19 You will be removed from your stewardship, and from your place. 
\v 20 It will come to pass in that day, that I will call my servant Eliakim the son of Chelcias: 
\v 21 and I will put on him your robe, and I will grant him your crown with power, and I will give your stewardship into his hands: and he will be like a father to those who dwell in Jerusalem, and to those who dwell in Judah. 
\v 22 I will give him the glory of David; and he will rule, and there will be none to speak against him: and I will give him the key \x + \xo 22:22 \xt Rev. 3. 7.\x*of the house of David \add upon\add* his shoulder; and he will open, and there will be none to shut; and he will shut, and there will be none to open. 
\v 23 I will make him a ruler in a sure place, and he will be for a glorious throne of his father's house. 
\v 24 Every one that is glorious in the house of his father will trust in him, from the least to the greatest; and they will depend upon him in that day. 
\v 25 Thus says the Lord of hosts, The man who is fastened in the sure place will be removed and be taken away, and will fall; and the glory that is upon him will be completely destroyed: for the Lord has spoken it. 
\c 23 
\d
\v 1 \sc The Word concerning Tyre.\sc* 
\p Howl, you ships of Carthage; for she has perished, and \add men\add* no longer arrive from the land of the Citians: she is led captive. 
\v 2 Who have the dwellers in the coastland become like, the merchants of Phœnice, passing over the sea 
\v 3 in great waters, a generation of merchants? As when the harvest is gathered in, \add so are\add* these traders with the nations. 
\v 4 Be ashamed, O Sidon: the sea has said, yes, the strength of the sea has said, I have not travailed, nor brought forth, nor have I brought up young men, nor reared virgins. 
\v 5 Moreover when it will be heard in Egypt, sorrow will seize them for Tyre. 
\v 6 Depart to Carthage; howl, you who dwell in this coastland. 
\v 7 Was not this your pride from the beginning, before she was given up? 
\v 8 Who has devised this counsel against Tyre? Is she inferior? Or has she no strength? Her merchants were the glorious princes of the earth. 
\p
\v 9 The Lord of hosts has purposed to bring down all the pride of the glorious ones, and to disgrace every glorious thing on the earth. 
\v 10 Till your land; for no ships come out of Carthage any more. 
\v 11 Your hand doesn't prevail by sea any more, which \f + \fr 23:11 \ft See chap \xt 5. 25; 14. 16.\f*troubled kings: the Lord of hosts has given a command concerning Canaan, to destroy the strength of it. 
\v 12 And \add men\add* will say, You will surely not continue to insult and injure the daughter of Sidon any longer: and if you depart to the Citians, you will not have rest there either. 
\v 13 And \add if you depart\add* to the land of the Chaldeans, this also is laid waste by the Assyrians, for her wall is fallen. 
\v 14 Howl, you ships of Carthage: for your stronghold is destroyed. 
\p
\v 15 It will come to pass in that day, \add that\add* Tyre will be left seventy years, as the time of a king, as the time of a man: and it will come to pass after seventy years, \add that\add* Tyre will be like the song of a prostitute. 
\v 16 Take a harp, go about, O city, you prostitute who has been forgotten; play well on the harp, sing many \add songs\add*, that you may be remembered. 
\v 17 It will come to pass after the seventy years, \add that\add* God will visit Tyre, and she will be again restored to her primitive state, and she will be a mart for all the kingdoms of the world on the face of the earth. 
\v 18 Her trade and her gain will be holiness to the Lord: it will not be gathered for them, but for those who dwell before the Lord, \add even\add* all her trade, to eat and drink and be filled, and for a covenant \add and\add* a memorial before the Lord. 
\c 24 
\p
\v 1 Behold, the Lord is about to lay waste the world, and will make it desolate, and will lay bare the surface of it, and scatter those who dwell therein. 
\v 2 The people will be like the priest, and the servant like the lord, and the maiden like the mistress; the buyer will be like the seller, the lender like the borrower, and the debtor like his creditor. 
\p
\v 3 The earth will be completely laid waste, and the earth will be completely spoiled: for the mouth of the Lord has spoken these things. 
\v 4 The earth mourns, and the world is ruined, the lofty ones of the earth are mourning. 
\v 5 She has sinned because of her inhabitants; because they have transgressed the law, and changed the ordinances, \add even\add* the everlasting covenant. 
\v 6 Therefore a curse will consume the earth, because the inhabitants of it have sinned: therefore the dwellers in the earth will be poor, and few men will be left. 
\v 7 The wine will mourn, the vine will mourn, all the merry-hearted will sigh. 
\v 8 The mirth of timbrels has ceased, the sound of the harp has ceased. 
\v 9 They are ashamed, they have not drunk wine; strong drink has become bitter to those who drink \add it\add*. 
\v 10 All the city has become desolate: one will shut his house so that none will enter. 
\v 11 There is a howling for the wine everywhere; all the mirth of the land has ceased, all the mirth of the land has departed. 
\v 12 Cities will be left desolate, and houses being left will fall to ruin. 
\p
\v 13 All this will be in the land among the nations, as if one should strip an olive tree, so will they strip them; but when the vintage is done, 
\v 14 these will cry aloud; and those who are left on the land will rejoice together in the glory of the Lord: the water of the sea will be troubled. 
\v 15 Therefore the glory of the Lord will be in the isles of the sea; the name of the Lord will be glorious. 
\p
\v 16 O Lord God of Israel, from the ends of the earth we have heard wonderful things, \add and there is\add* hope to the godly: but they will say, Woe to the despisers, that despise the law. 
\v 17 Fear, and a pit, and a snare, are upon you who dwell on the earth. 
\v 18 It will come to pass, \add that\add* he who flees from the fear will fall into the pit; and he who comes up out of the pit will be caught by the snare: for windows have been opened in heaven, and the foundations of the earth will be shaken, 
\v 19 the earth will be completely greatly agitated, and the earth will be completely perplexed. 
\v 20 It reels like a drunkard and one oppressed with wine, and the earth will be shaken like a storehouse of fruits; for wickedness has prevailed upon it, and it will fall, and will not be able to rise. 
\p
\v 21 God will bring \add his\add* hand upon the host of heaven, and upon the kings of the earth. 
\v 22 They will gather the multitude of it into prisons, and they will shut them into a stronghold: after many generations they will be visited. 
\v 23 The brick will decay, and the wall will fall; for the Lord will reign \f + \fr 24:23 \fqa Heb. \ft and \fqa Alex. \ft ‘in’.\f*from out of Zion, and out of Jerusalem, and will be glorified before \add his\add* elders. 
\c 25 
\p
\v 1 O Lord God, I will glorify you, I will sing to your name; for you have done wonderful things, \add even\add* an ancient \add and\add* faithful counsel. So be it. 
\v 2 For you have made cities a heap, \add even\add* cities \add made\add* strong that their foundations should not fall: the city of ungodly men will not be built forever. 
\v 3 Therefore the poor people will bless you, and cities of injured men will bless you. 
\v 4 For you have been a helper to every lowly city, and a shelter to those who were disheartened because of poverty: you will deliver them from wicked men: \add you have been\add* a shelter of those who thirst, and a refreshing air to injured men. 
\p
\v 5 \add We were\add* as faint-hearted men thirsting in Zion, because of ungodly men to whom you delivered us. 
\v 6 The Lord of hosts will make \add a feast\add* for all the nations: on this mount they will drink gladness, they will drink wine: 
\v 7 they will anoint themselves with ointment in this mountain. Impart all these things to the nations; for this is \add God's\add* counsel upon all the nations. 
\v 8 \x + \xo 25:8 \xt 1 Cor. 15. 54.\x*Death has prevailed and swallowed \add men\add* up; but again the Lord God has taken away every tear from every face. He has taken away the reproach of \add his\add* people from all the earth: for the mouth of the Lord has spoken it. 
\v 9 In that day they will say, Behold our God in whom we have trusted, and he will save us: this \add is\add* the Lord; we have waited for him, and we have exulted, and will rejoice in our salvation. 
\p
\v 10 God will give rest on this mountain, and the country of Moab will be trodden down, as they tread the floor with waggons. 
\v 11 He will spread forth his hands, even as he also brings down \add man\add* to destroy \add him\add*: and he will bring low his pride \add in regard to the thing\add* on which he has laid his hands. 
\v 12 He will bring down the height of the refuge of the wall, and it will come down even to the ground. 
\c 26 
\p
\v 1 In that day they will sing this song in the land of Judea; Behold a strong city; and he will make salvation \add its\add* wall and bulwark. 
\v 2 Open the gates, let the nation enter that keeps righteousness, and keeps truth, 
\v 3 supporting truth, and keeping peace: for on you, O Lord, 
\v 4 they have trusted with confidence forever, the great, the eternal God; 
\v 5 who have humbled and brought down those who dwell on high, you will cast down strong cities, and bring them to the ground. 
\v 6 The feet of the meek and lowly will trample them. 
\p
\v 7 The way of the godly is made straight: the way of the godly is also prepared. 
\v 8 For the way of the Lord is judgment: we have hoped in your name, and on the remembrance \add of you\add*, 
\v 9 which our soul longs for: my spirit seeks you very early in the morning, O God, for your commandments are a light on the earth: learn righteousness, you who dwell upon the earth. 
\v 10 For the ungodly one is put down: no one who will not learn righteousness on the earth, can do the truth: let the ungodly be taken away, that he not see the glory of the Lord. 
\v 11 O Lord, your arm is exalted, yet they didn't know it: but when they know they will be ashamed: zeal will seize upon an untaught nation, and now fire will devour the adversaries. 
\v 12 O Lord our God, give us peace: for you have rendered to us all things. 
\v 13 O Lord our God, take possession of us: O Lord, we don't know \add any\add* other beside you: we name your name. 
\p
\v 14 But the dead will not see life, neither will \f + \fr 26:14 \ft See \xt Job 26. 5.\f*physicians by any means raise \add them\add* up: therefore you have brought \add wrath\add* upon \add them\add*, and killed \add them\add*, and have taken away every male of them. Bring more evils upon them, O Lord; 
\v 15 bring more evils on the glorious ones of the earth. 
\p
\v 16 Lord, in affliction I remembered you; your chastening was to us with small affliction. 
\v 17 As a woman in labor draws near to be delivered, \add and\add* cries out in her pain; so have we been to your beloved. 
\v 18 We have conceived, O Lord, because of your fear, and have been in pain, and have brought forth the breath of your salvation, which we have worked upon the earth: we will not fall, but all that dwell upon the land will fall. 
\v 19 The dead will rise, and those who are in the tombs will be raised, and those who are in the earth will rejoice: for \f + \fr 26:19 \ft See \xt Ps. 110.\f*the dew from you is healing to them: but the land of the ungodly will perish. 
\v 20 Go, my people, enter into your closets, shut your door, hide yourself for a little season, until the anger of the Lord has passed away. 
\v 21 For, behold, the Lord is bringing wrath from \add his\add* holy place upon the dwellers on the earth: the earth also will disclose her blood, and will not cover her killed. 
\c 27 
\p
\v 1 In that day God will bring \add his\add* holy and great and strong sword upon the dragon, even the snake that flees, upon the dragon, the crooked snake: he will destroy the dragon. 
\v 2 In that day \add there will be\add* a fair vineyard, \add and\add* a desire to commence \add a song\add* concerning it. 
\v 3 I am a strong city, a city in a siege: in vain I will water it; for it will be taken by night, and by day the wall will fall. 
\v 4 There is no woman that has not taken hold of it; who will set me to watch stubble in the field? Because of this enemy I have set her aside; therefore on this account the Lord has done all that he appointed. 
\v 5 I am burnt up; those who dwell in her will cry, Let us make peace with him, let us make peace, 
\v 6 those who are coming are the children of Jacob. Israel will bud and blossom, and the world will be filled with his fruit. 
\p
\v 7 Will he himself be thus struck, even as he struck? And as he killed, will he be thus killed? 
\v 8 Fighting and reproaching he will dismiss them; did you not meditate with a harsh spirit, to kill them with a wrathful spirit? 
\v 9 Therefore will the wickedness of Jacob be taken away; and this is his blessing, when I will have taken away his sin; when they will have broken to pieces all the stones of the altars like fine dust, and their trees will not remain, and their idols will be cut off, like a thicket afar off. 
\v 10 The flock that dwelt \add there\add* will be left, like a deserted flock; and \add the ground\add* will be for a long time for pasture, and there will flocks lie down to rest. 
\v 11 After a time there will be in it no green thing because of \add the grass\add* being parched. Come here, you women who come \f + \fr 27:11 \ft See \fqa Heb.\f*from a sight; for it is a people of no understanding; therefore he who made them will have no pity upon them, and he who formed them will have no mercy \add upon them\add*. 
\p
\v 12 It will come to pass in that day \add that\add* God will fence \add men\add* off from the channel of the river as far as Rhinocorura; but you, gather one by one the children of Israel. 
\v 13 It will come to pass in that day, \add that\add* they will blow the great trumpet, and the lost ones in the land of the Assyrians will come, and the lost ones in Egypt, and will worship the Lord on the holy mountain in Jerusalem. 
\c 28 
\p
\v 1 Woe to the crown of pride, the hirelings of Ephraim, the flower that has fallen from the glory of the top of the fertile mountain, those who are drunk without wine. 
\v 2 Behold, the anger of the Lord is strong and severe, like descending hail where there is no shelter, violently descending; like a great body of water sweeping away the soil, he will make rest for the land. 
\v 3 The crown of pride, the hirelings of Ephraim, will be beaten down with the hands and with the feet. 
\v 4 The fading flower of the \f + \fr 28:4 \fqa Gr. \ft hope of glory.\f*glorious hope on the top of the high mountain will be like the early fig; he who sees it, before he takes it into his hand, will desire to swallow it down. 
\p
\v 5 In that day the Lord of hosts will be the crown of hope, the woven \add crown\add* of glory, to the remnant of the people. 
\v 6 They will be left in the spirit of judgment for judgment, and for the strength of those who hinder killing. 
\v 7 For these have trespassed through wine; they have erred through strong drink: the priest and the prophet are mad through strong drink, they are swallowed up because of wine, they have staggered \f + \fr 28:7 \fqa Lit. \ft from.\f*through drunkenness; they have erred: this is \add their\add* vision. 
\v 8 A curse will devour this counsel, for this \add is their\add* counsel for the sake of covetousness. 
\v 9 To whom have we reported evils? And to whom have we reported a message? \add even to those\add* who are weaned from the milk, who are drawn from the breast. 
\v 10 Expect affliction on affliction, hope upon hope: yet a little, \add and\add* yet a little, 
\v 11 \x + \xo 28:11 \xt 1 Cor. 14. 21.\x*because of the contemptuous \add words\add* of the lips, by means of another language: for they will speak to this people, saying to them, 
\v 12 This is the rest to him who is hungry, and this is the calamity: but they would not hear. 
\p
\v 13 Therefore the oracle of God will be to them affliction on affliction, hope on hope, yet a little, \add and\add* yet a little, so they may go and fall backward; and they will be crushed and will be in danger, and will be taken. 
\p
\v 14 Therefore hear the word of the Lord, you afflicted men, and you princes of this people that is in Jerusalem. 
\v 15 Because you have said, We have made a covenant with Hades, and agreements with death; if the rushing storm should pass, it will not come upon us: we have made falsehood our hope, and by falsehood will we be protected: 
\v 16 therefore thus says the Lord, \add even\add* the Lord, 
\p \x + \xo 28:16 \xt Rom. 9. 33; 1 Pet. 2. 6.\x*Behold, I lay for the foundations of Zion a costly stone, a choice, a corner-stone, a precious \add stone\add*, for its foundations; and he who believes \add on him\add* will by no means be ashamed. 
\v 17 I will cause judgment \add to be\add* for hope, and my compassion will be for \add just\add* measures, and you who trust vainly in falsehood \add will fall\add*: for the storm will by no means pass by you, 
\v 18 \f + \fr 28:18 \fqa Or, \ft shall it not also? etc.\f*except it also take away your covenant of death, and your trust in Hades will by no means stand: if the rushing storm should come upon you, you will be beaten down by it. 
\v 19 Whenever it will pass by, it will take you; morning by morning it will pass by in the day, and in the night there will be an evil hope. 
\p Learn to hear, 
\v 20 you who are distressed; we cannot fight, but we are ourselves too weak for you to be gathered. 
\v 21 The Lord will rise up like a mountain of ungodly \add men\add*, and will be in the valley of Gabaon; he will perform his works with wrath, \add even\add* a work of bitterness, and his wrath will deal strangely, and his destruction will be foreign. 
\v 22 Therefore do not rejoice, neither let your bands be made strong; for I have heard of works finished and cut short by the Lord of hosts, which he will execute upon all the earth. 
\p
\v 23 Listen, and hear my voice; pay attention, and hear my words. 
\v 24 Will the ploughman plough all the day? Or will he prepare the seed beforehand, before he tills the ground? 
\v 25 Does he not, when he has levelled the surface of it, then sow the small black poppy, or cumin, and afterward sow wheat, and barley, and millet, and bread-grain in your borders? 
\v 26 So you will be chastened by the judgment of your God, and will rejoice. 
\v 27 For the black poppy isn't cleansed with harsh treatment, nor will a waggon-wheel pass over the cumin; but the black poppy is threshed with a rod, and the cumin will be eaten with bread; 
\v 28 for \f + \fr 28:28 \fqa Gr. \ft I am.\f*I will not be angry with you forever, neither will the voice of \f + \fr 28:28 \fqa Gr. \ft bitterness trample you.\f*my anger crush you. 
\v 29 These signs came forth from the Lord of hosts. Take counsel; raise a vain appeal. 
\c 29 
\p
\v 1 \f + \fr 29:1 \fqa Or, \ft woe to.\f*Alas for the city Ariel, which David \f + \fr 29:1 \ft See \fqa Heb.\f*besieged. Gather fruits year by year; eat, for you will eat with Moab. 
\v 2 For I will grievously afflict Ariel: and her strength and her wealth will be mine. 
\v 3 I will surround you as David \add did\add*, and will raise a mound about you, and set up towers round you. 
\v 4 Your words will be brought down to the earth, and your words will sink down to the earth, and your voice will be like those who speak out of the earth, and your voice will \f + \fr 29:4 \fqa Gr. \ft become weak.\f*be lowered to the ground. 
\v 5 But the wealth of the ungodly will be like dust from a wheel, and the multitude of those who oppress you like flying chaff, and it will be suddenly like a moment, 
\v 6 from the Lord of hosts: for there will be a visitation with thunder, and earthquake, and a loud \f + \fr 29:6 \fqa Gr. \ft voice.\f*noise, a rushing tempest, and devouring flame of fire. 
\v 7 The wealth of all the nations together, as many as have fought against Ariel, and all those who war against Jerusalem, and all who are gathered against her, and those who distress her, will be like one who dreams in sleep by night. 
\v 8 As men drink and eat in sleep, and when they have arisen, the dream is vain: and as a thirsty man dreams as if he drank, and having arisen is still thirsty, and his soul has desired in vain: so will be the wealth of all the nations, as many as have fought against the mount Zion. 
\p
\v 9 Faint and be amazed, and be overpowered, not with strong drink nor with wine. 
\v 10 For the Lord has made you to drink a spirit of deep sleep; and he will close their eyes, and \add the eyes\add* of their prophets and of their rulers, who see secret things. 
\v 11 All these things will be to you like the words of this sealed book, which if they will give to a learned man, saying, Read this, he will then say, I cannot read \add it\add*, for it is sealed. 
\v 12 This book will be given into the hands of a man who doesn't know letters, and \add one\add* will say to him, Read this; and he will say, I don't know letters. 
\p
\v 13 The Lord has said, \x + \xo 29:13 \xt Mat. 8. 9.\x*This people draw near to me with their mouth, and they honour me with their lips, but their heart is far from me: but in vain do they worship me, teaching the commandments and doctrines of men. 
\v 14 Therefore behold I will proceed to remove this people, and I will remove them: and \x + \xo 29:14 \xt 1 Cor. 1. 19.\x*I will destroy the wisdom of the wise, and will hide the understanding of the prudent. 
\v 15 Woe to those who deepen their counsel, and not by the Lord. Woe to those who take secret counsel, and whose works \f + \fr 29:15 \fqa Gr. \ft shall be.\f*are in darkness, and they say, Who has seen us? And who will know us, or what we do? 
\v 16 Will you not be counted as clay of the potter? \x + \xo 29:16 \xt Rom. 9. 20.\x*Will the thing formed say to him who formed it, You did not form me? Or the work to the maker, You have not made me wisely? 
\v 17 \add Is it\add* not yet a little while, and Lebanon will be changed like the mountain of Chermel, and Chermel will be reckoned as a forest? 
\v 18 In that day the deaf will hear the words of the book, and those who are in darkness, and those who are in mist: the eyes of the blind will see, 
\v 19 and the poor will rejoice with joy because of the Lord, and those who had no hope among men will be filled with joy. 
\v 20 The lawless man has come to nought, and the proud man has perished, and those who transgress mischievously have been completely destroyed: 
\v 21 and those who cause men to sin by a word: and men will make all that reprove in the gates an offence, because they have unjustly turned aside the righteous. 
\p
\v 22 Therefore thus says the Lord concerning the house of Jacob, whom he set apart from Abraham, Jacob will not now be ashamed, neither he will now \f + \fr 29:22 \ft `change face' suggests losing composure, a parallel to being ashamed.\f*change face. 
\v 23 But when their children have seen my works, they will sanctify my name for my sake, and they will sanctify the Holy One of Jacob, and will fear the God of Israel. 
\v 24 Those who erred in spirit will know understanding, and the murmurers will learn obedience, and the stammering tongues will learn to speak peace. 
\c 30 
\p
\v 1 Woe to the apostate children, says the Lord: you have framed counsel, not by me, and covenants not by my Spirit, to add sins to sins: 
\v 2 \add even\add* those who proceed to go down into Egypt, but they have not enquired of me, that they might be helped by Pharaoh, and protected by the Egyptians. 
\v 3 For the protection of Pharaoh will be to you a disgrace, and \add there will be\add* a reproach to those who trust in Egypt. 
\v 4 For there are princes in Tanes, evil messengers. 
\v 5 In vain will they labour \add in seeking\add* to a people, which will not profit them for help, but \add will be\add* for a shame and reproach. 
\d
\v 6 \sc The Vision of the \f + \fr 30:6 \fqa Gr. \ft Quadrupeds\f*Beasts in the Desert.\sc* 
\p In affliction and distress, \add where are\add* the lion and lion's cub, from there \add come\add* also asps, and the young of flying asps, \add there they will be\add* who bore their wealth on donkeys and camels to a nation which will not profit them. 
\v 7 The Egyptians will help you completely in vain: tell them, This your consolation is vain. 
\p
\v 8 Now then sit down and write these words on a tablet, and in a book; for these things will be \f + \fr 30:8 \fqa Gr. \ft for days in time. \fqa Alex. \ft seasons.\f*for \add many long\add* days, and even forever. 
\v 9 For the people are disobedient, false children, who would not hear the law of God: 
\v 10 who say to the prophets, Don't report to us; and to those who see visions, Don't speak \add them\add* to us, but speak and report to us another error; 
\v 11 and turn us aside from this way; remove from us this path, and remove from us the oracle of Israel. 
\p
\v 12 Therefore thus says the Holy One of Israel, Because you have refused to obey these words, and have trusted in falsehood; and because you have murmured, and been confident in this respect: 
\v 13 therefore this sin will be to you like a wall suddenly falling when a strong city has been taken, of which the fall is very near at hand. 
\v 14 The fall of it will be like the breaking of an earthen vessel, \add as\add* small fragments of a pitcher, so that you should not find among them a sherd, with which you might take up fire, and with which you should draw a little water. 
\p
\v 15 Thus says the Lord, the Holy Lord of Israel; When you will turn and mourn, then you will be saved; and you will know where you were, when you trusted in vanities: \add then\add* your strength became vain, yet you would not listen: 
\v 16 but you said, We will flee upon horses; therefore you will flee: and, We will be aided by swift riders; therefore those who pursue you will be swift. 
\v 17 A thousand will flee because of the voice of one, and many will flee on account of the voice of five; until you are left like a signal-post upon a mountain, and like one bearing an ensign upon a hill. 
\p
\v 18 The Lord will again wait, that he may pity you, and will therefore be exalted that he may have mercy upon you: because the Lord your God is a judge: blessed are those who \f + \fr 30:18 \fqa Or, \ft wait for.\f*stay themselves upon him. 
\p
\v 19 For the holy people will dwell in Zion: and \add because\add* Jerusalem has \f + \fr 30:19 \fqa Gr. \ft with weeping.\f*wept bitterly, \add saying\add*, Pity me; he will pity you: when he perceived the voice of your cry, he listened to you. 
\v 20 And \add though\add* the Lord will give you the bread of affliction and scant water, yet those who cause you to err will surely not draw near to you any more; for your eyes will see those that cause you to err, 
\v 21 and your ears will hear the words of those who went after you to lead you astray, who say, This \add is\add* the way, let us walk in it, whether to the right or to the left. 
\v 22 You will remove the idols overlaid with silver and overlaid with gold, and you will grind them to powder, and you will scatter them like used water that has been poured away, and you will thrust them forth like dung. 
\v 23 Then will there be rain to the seed of your land; and the bread of the fruit of your land will be plenteous and rich: and your cattle will feed in that day in a fertile and spacious place. 
\v 24 Your bulls and your oxen that till the ground, will eat chaff mixed with winnowed barley. 
\v 25 There will be running water on every lofty mountain and on every high hill in that day, when many will perish, and when the towers will fall. 
\v 26 The light of the moon will be like the light of the sun, and the light of the sun will be sevenfold in the day when the Lord will heal the breach of his people, and will heal the pain of your wound. 
\p
\v 27 Behold, the name of the Lord comes after a \add long\add* time, burning wrath: the word of his lips is with glory, a word full of anger, and the anger of his wrath will devour like fire. 
\v 28 His breath, like rushing water in a valley, will reach as far as the neck, and be divided, to confound the nations for \add their\add* vain error: error also will pursue them, and \f + \fr 30:28 \fqa Gr. \ft take them to their face.\f*overtake them. 
\v 29 Must you always rejoice, and go into my holy places continually, like those who keep a feast? And must you go with a flute, as those who rejoice, into the mountain of the Lord, to the God of Israel? 
\v 30 The Lord will make his glorious voice to be heard, and the wrath of his arm, to make a display with wrath and anger and devouring flame: he will lighten terribly, and \add his wrath will be\add* like water and violent hail. 
\v 31 For by the voice of the Lord the Assyrians will be overcome, \add even\add* by the stroke with which he will strike them. 
\v 32 It will happen to him from every side, \add that\add* they from whom their hope of assistance was, in which he trusted, themselves will war against him in turn with drums and with harp. 
\v 33 For you will be required before \add your\add* time: has it been prepared for you also to reign? No, God has \add prepared for you\add* a deep pit, wood piled, fire and much wood: the wrath of the Lord \add will be\add* like a pit kindled with sulphur. 
\c 31 
\p
\v 1 Woe to those who go down to Egypt for help, who trust in horses and chariots, for they are many; and in horses, \add which are\add* a great multitude; and have not trusted in the Holy One of Israel, and have not sought the Lord. 
\v 2 Therefore he has wisely brought evils upon them, and his word will not be frustrated; and he will rise up against the houses of wicked men, and against their vain hope, 
\v 3 \add even\add* an Egyptian, a man, and not God; the flesh of horses, and there is no help \add in them\add*: but the Lord will bring his hand upon them, and the helpers will fail, and all will perish together. 
\v 4 For thus said the Lord to me, Like a lion would roar, or a lion's cub over prey which he has taken, and cry over it, until the mountains are filled with his voice, and \add the animals\add* are awe-struck and tremble at the fierceness of his wrath: so the Lord of hosts will descend to fight upon the mount Zion, \add even\add* upon her mountains. 
\v 5 Like birds flying, so will the Lord of hosts defend; he will defend Jerusalem, and he will rescue, and save and deliver. 
\v 6 Turn, you children of Israel, who devise a deep and sinful counsel. 
\v 7 For in that day men will renounce their silver idols and \add their\add* golden idols, which their hands made. 
\v 8 The Assyrian will fall: not the sword of a great man, nor the sword of a mean man will devour him; neither will he flee from the face of the sword: but the young men will be overthrown: 
\v 9 for they will be surrounded with rocks as with a palisade, and will be defeated; and he who flees will be taken. Thus says the Lord, Blessed is he who has a seed in Zion, and household friends in Jerusalem. 
\c 32 
\p
\v 1 For, behold, a righteous king will reign, and princes will govern with judgment. 
\v 2 A man will hide his words, and be hidden, as from rushing water, and will appear in Zion as a rushing river, glorious in a thirsty land. 
\v 3 They will no more trust in men, but they will incline their ears to hear. 
\v 4 The heart of the weak ones will pay attention to hear, and the stammering tongues will soon learn to speak peace. 
\v 5 Never again will they tell a fool to rule, and your servants will never again say, Be silent. 
\v 6 For the fool will speak foolish words, and his heart will meditate vanities, and to perform lawless deeds and to speak error against the Lord, to scatter hungry souls, and he will cause the thirsty souls to be empty. 
\v 7 For the counsel of the wicked will devise wickedness, to destroy the poor with unjust words, and \f + \fr 32:7 \fqa Gr. \ft disperse the words.\f*ruin the cause of the poor in judgment. 
\v 8 But the godly have devised wise \add measures\add*, and this counsel will stand. 
\p
\v 9 Rise up, you rich women, and hear my voice; \f + \fr 32:9 \fqa Gr. \ft daughters in hope.\f*you confident daughters, listen to my words. 
\v 10 Remember for a full year in pain, yet with hope: the vintage has been cut off, it has ceased, it will by no means come again. 
\v 11 Be shaken, be distressed, you confident women: strip yourself, become naked, gird your loins with sackcloth; 
\v 12 and beat on your breasts, because of the pleasant field, and the fruit of the vine. 
\v 13 \add As for\add* the land of my people, the thorn and grass will come upon \add it\add*, and joy will be removed from every house. 
\v 14 \add As for\add* the rich city, the houses are deserted; they will abandon the wealth of the city, \add and\add* the pleasant houses: and the villages will be caves forever, the joy of wild donkeys, shepherds' pastures; 
\v 15 until the Spirit will come upon you from on high, and Chermel will be desert, and Chermel will be counted for a forest. 
\v 16 Then judgment will abide in the wilderness, and righteousness will dwell in Carmel. 
\v 17 The works of righteousness will be peace; and righteousness will ensure rest, and \add the righteous\add* will be confident forever. 
\v 18 His people will inhabit a city of peace, and dwell in \add it\add* in confidence, and they will rest with wealth. 
\v 19 If the hail should come down, it will not come upon you; and those who dwell in the forests will be confident like those in the plain country. 
\v 20 Blessed are those who sow by every water, where the ox and ass tread. 
\c 33 
\p
\v 1 Woe to those who afflict you; but no one makes you afflicted: and he who deals treacherously with you does not deal treacherously: those who deal treacherously will be taken and given up, and like a moth on a garment, so they will be defeated. 
\p
\v 2 Lord, have mercy upon us; for we have trusted in you: the seed of the rebellious has gone to destruction, but our deliverance was in a time of affliction. 
\v 3 Because of the terrible sound the nations were dismayed for fear of you, and the nations were scattered. 
\p
\v 4 Now the spoils of your small and great will be gathered: as if one should gather locusts, so will they mock you. 
\v 5 The God who dwells on high is holy: Zion is filled with judgment and righteousness. 
\v 6 They will be delivered up to the law: our salvation is our treasure: there are \add found\add* wisdom and knowledge and piety toward the Lord; these are the treasures of righteousness. 
\p
\v 7 Behold now, they themselves will be terrified with fear of you: those whom you feared will cry out because of you: messengers will be sent, asking for peace, bitterly weeping, entreating for peace. 
\v 8 For their ways will be made desolate: the terror of the nations has been made to cease, and the covenant with these is taken away, and you will by no means regard them as men. 
\v 9 The land mourns; Lebanon is ashamed: Saron is become marshes; Galilee will be \f + \fr 33:9 \fqa Gr. \ft manifest.\f*laid bare, and Chermel. 
\p
\v 10 Now I will arise, says the Lord, now I will be glorified; now I will be exalted. 
\v 11 Now you will see, now you will perceive; the strength of your breath will be vain; fire will devour you. 
\v 12 The nations will be burnt up; like a thorn in the field cast out and burnt up. 
\p
\v 13 Those who are afar off will hear what I have done; those who draw near will know my strength. 
\v 14 The sinners in Zion have departed; trembling will seize the ungodly. Who will tell you that a fire is kindled? Who will tell you of the eternal place? 
\p
\v 15 The one walking in righteousness, speaking rightly, hating transgression and wickedness, and shaking his hands from gifts, stopping his ears that he should not hear the judgment of blood, shutting his eyes that he should not see injustice; 
\v 16 he will dwell in a high cave of a strong rock: bread will be given him, and his water will be sure. 
\v 17 You will see a king with glory: your eyes will behold a land from afar. 
\v 18 Your soul will meditate terror. Where are the scribes? Where are the counsellors, where is he who numbers those who are growing up, 
\v 19 \add even\add* the small and great people? With whom he took no counsel, neither did he understand \add a people\add* of deep speech, so that a despised people should not hear, and there is no understanding to him that hears. 
\p
\v 20 Behold the city Zion, \f + \fr 33:20 \fqa Or, \ft salvation.\f*our refuge: your eyes will behold Jerusalem, a rich city, tents which will not be shaken, neither will her tent-pegs ever be moved, and her cords will surely not be broken: 
\v 21 for the name of the Lord is great to you: you will have a place, \add even\add* rivers and wide and spacious channels: you will not go this way, neither a vessel with oars go \add there\add*. 
\v 22 For my God is great: the Lord our judge will not pass me by: the Lord is our prince, the Lord is our king; the Lord, he will save us. 
\p
\v 23 Your cords are broken, for they had no strength: your mast has given way, it will not spread the sails, it will not bear a signal, until it be given up for plunder; therefore many lame men will take spoil. 
\v 24 The people dwelling among them will surely not say, \f + \fr 33:24 \fqa Or, \ft I am sick.\f*I am in pain: for their sin will be forgiven them. 
\c 34 
\p
\v 1 Draw near, you nations; and listen, you princes; let the earth hear, and those who are in it; the world, and the people in it. 
\v 2 For the wrath of the Lord is upon all nations, and \add his\add* anger on their \add entire\add* number, to destroy them, and give them up to slaughter. 
\v 3 Their killed will be cast forth, and their corpses; and their smell will rise up, and the mountains will be made wet with their blood. 
\v 4 All the powers of the heavens will melt, and the sky will be rolled up like a scroll: and all the stars will fall like leaves from a vine, and like leaves fall from a fig-tree. 
\p
\v 5 My sword has been made drunk in heaven: behold, it will come down upon Idumea, and with judgment upon the people doomed to destruction. 
\v 6 The sword of the Lord is filled with blood, it is glutted with fat, with the blood of goats and lambs, and with the fat of goats and rams: for the Lord has a sacrifice in Bosor, and a great slaughter in Idumea. 
\v 7 The mighty ones will fall with them, and the rams and the bulls; and the land will be \f + \fr 34:7 \fqa Gr. \ft made drunk.\f*soaked with blood, and will be filled with their fat. 
\v 8 For it is the day of the judgment of the Lord, and the year of the recompence of Zion in judgment. 
\v 9 Her valleys will be turned into pitch, and her land into sulphur; and her land will be as pitch burning night and day; 
\v 10 and it will never be quenched, and her smoke will go up: it will be made desolate throughout her generations, 
\v 11 and for a long time birds and hedgehogs, and ibises and ravens will dwell in it: and the measuring line of desolation will be cast over it, and \f + \fr 34:11 \fqa See above, \xt 13. 22.\f*onocentaurs will dwell in it. 
\v 12 Her princes will be no more; for her kings and her great men will be destroyed. 
\v 13 Thorns will spring up in their cities, and in her strong holds: and they will be habitations of \f + \fr 34:13 \fqa See above, \xt Job 30. 29; Is. 13. 21, \ft etc., especially the note to Isa 13:21 above.\f*sirens, and a court for birds. 
\v 14 Demons will meet with onocentaurs, and they will cry one to the other: there onocentaurs will rest, having found for themselves \add a place of\add* rest. 
\v 15 There the \f + \fr 34:15 \ft The precise animal is uncertain. The Greek ἐχῖνος probably refers to a hedgehog-like desert animal.\f*hedgehog has made its nest, and the earth has safely preserved its young: there the deer have met, and seen one another's faces. 
\v 16 They passed by in \add full\add* number, and not one of them perished: they didn't seek one another; for the Lord commanded them, and his Spirit gathered them. 
\v 17 He will cast lots for them, and his hand has portioned out \add their\add* pasture, \add saying\add*, You will inherit \add the land\add* forever: they will rest on it \add through\add* all generations. 
\c 35 
\p
\v 1 Be glad, you thirsty desert: let the wilderness exult, and flower like the lily. 
\v 2 The desert places of Jordan will blossom and rejoice; the glory of Lebanon has been given to it, and the honour of Carmel; and my people will see the glory of the Lord, and the majesty of God. 
\p
\v 3 \x + \xo 35:3 \xt Heb. 12. 12.\x*Be strong, you drooping hands and palsied knees. 
\v 4 Comfort one another, you faint-hearted; be strong, don't be afraid; behold, our God renders judgment, and he will give \add it\add*; he will come and save us. 
\v 5 Then the eyes of the blind will be opened, and the ears of the deaf will hear. 
\v 6 Then the lame man will leap like a hart, and the tongue of the stammerers will speak plainly; for water has burst forth in the desert, and a channel \add of water\add* in a thirsty land. 
\v 7 The dry land will become pools, and a fountain of water will \add be poured\add* into the thirsty land; there will there be a joy of birds, ready habitations and marshes. 
\v 8 There will be there a pure way, and it will be called a holy way; and no unclean person will pass by there, neither will there be an unclean way there; but the dispersed will walk on it, and they will not go astray. 
\v 9 There will be no lion there, neither will any evil beast go up upon it nor be found there at all; but the redeemed and gathered on the Lord's behalf, will walk in it, 
\v 10 and will return, and come to Zion with joy, and everlasting joy \add will be\add* over their head; for on their head \add will be\add* praise and exultation, and joy will take possession of them: sorrow and pain, and groaning have fled away. 
\c 36 
\p
\v 1 Now it happened in the fourteenth year of the reign of Hezekiah, \add that\add* Sennacherim, king of the Assyrians, came up against the strong cities of Judea, and took them. 
\v 2 The king of the Assyrians sent Rabsaces out of Laches to Jerusalem to king Hezekiah with a large force: and he stood by the \f + \fr 36:2 \fqa Gr. \ft in.\f*conduit of the upper pool in the way of the fuller's field. 
\v 3 Heliakim the steward, the \add son\add* of Chelcias went out to him, with Somnas the scribe, and Joach the \add son\add* of Asaph, the recorder. 
\p
\v 4 Rabsaces said to them, Say to Hezekiah, Thus says the great king, the king of the Assyrians, Why are you secure? 
\v 5 Is war carried on with counsel and \add mere\add* words of the lips? And now on whom do you trust, that you rebel against me? 
\v 6 Behold, you trust on this bruised staff of reed, on Egypt: \add as soon\add* as a man leans upon it, it will go into his hand, and pierce it: so is Pharaoh king of Egypt and all that trust in him. 
\v 7 But if you say, We trust in the Lord our God; 
\v 8 yet now make an agreement with my lord the king of the Assyrians, and I will give you two thousand horses, if you can set riders upon them. 
\v 9 How can you \add then\add* turn to the face of the \f + \fr 36:9 \fqa Or, \ft local governors.\f*satraps? Those who trust on the Egyptians for horse and rider are \add our\add* servants. 
\v 10 Now, Have we come up against this land to fight against it without the Lord? The Lord said to me, Go up against this land, and destroy it. 
\p
\v 11 Then Eliakim and Somnas and Joach said to him, Speak to your servants in the Syrian tongue; for we understand \add it\add*: and don't speak to us in the Jewish tongue: and why do you speak in the ears of the men on the wall? 
\v 12 Rabsaces said to them, Has my lord sent me to your lord or to you, to speak these words? \add has he\add* not \add sent\add* me to the men who sit on the wall, so they may eat dung, and drink \add their\add* water together with you? 
\p
\v 13 Rabsaces stood, and cried with a loud voice in the Jewish language, and said, Hear the words of the great king, the king of the Assyrians: 
\v 14 thus says the king, Don't let Hezekiah deceive you with words: he will not be able to deliver you. 
\v 15 Don't let Hezekiah say to you, God will deliver you, and this city will not at all be delivered into the hand of the king of the Assyrians. 
\v 16 Don't listen to Hezekiah: thus says the king of the Assyrians, If you wish to be blessed, come out to me: and you will eat every one \add of\add* his vine and his fig-trees, and you will drink water out of your own cisterns; 
\v 17 until I come and take you to a land, like your own land, a land of grain and wine, and bread and vineyards. 
\v 18 Don't let Hezekiah deceive you, saying, God will deliver you. Have the gods of the nations delivered each one his own land out of the hand of the king of the Assyrians? 
\v 19 Where is the god of Emath, and Arphath? And where is the god of Eppharuaim? Have they been able to deliver Samaria out of my hand? 
\v 20 Which god of all these nations has delivered his land out of my hand, that God should deliver Jerusalem out of my hand? 
\v 21 They were silent, and no one answered him a word; because the king had commanded that no one should answer. 
\p
\v 22 Heliakim the \add son\add* of Chelcias, the steward, and Somnas the military scribe, and Joach the \add son\add* of Asaph, the recorder, came in to Hezekiah, having their garments torn, and they reported to him the words of Rabsaces. 
\c 37 
\p
\v 1 It happened, when king Hezekiah heard \add it, that\add* he tore his clothes, and put on sackcloth, and went up to the house of the Lord. 
\p
\v 2 He sent Heliakim the steward, and Somnas the scribe, and the elders of the priests clothed with sackcloth, to Isaiah the son of Amos, the prophet. And they said to him, Thus says Hezekiah, 
\v 3 Today is a day of affliction, and reproach, and rebuke, and anger: for the pangs have come upon the \add woman\add* in labour, but she doesn't have strength to bring forth. 
\v 4 May the Lord your God hear the words of Rabsaces, which the king of the Assyrians has sent, to reproach the living God, even to reproach with the words which the Lord your God has heard: therefore you will pray to your Lord for these that are left. 
\p
\v 5 So the servants of king Hezekiah came to Isaiah. 
\v 6 Isaiah said to them, Thus will you say to your master, Thus says the Lord, Don't be afraid at the words which you have heard, with which the ambassadors of the king of the Assyrians have reproached me. 
\v 7 Behold, I \add will\add* send a blast upon him, and he will hear a report, and return to his own country, and he will fall by the sword in his own land. 
\p
\v 8 So Rabsaces returned, and found the king of the Assyrians besieging Lobna: for he had heard that he had departed from Lachis. 
\v 9 Tharaca king of the Ethiopians went out to \f + \fr 37:9 \fqa Gr. \ft besiege.\f*attack him. And when he heard it, he turned aside, and sent messengers to Hezekiah, saying, 
\v 10 Thus will you say to Hezekiah king of Judea, Don't let your God in whom you trust deceive you, saying, Jerusalem will not be delivered into the hand of the king of the Assyrians. 
\p
\v 11 Have you not heard what the kings of the Assyrians have done, how they have destroyed the whole earth? And will you be delivered? 
\v 12 Have the gods of the nations which my fathers destroyed delivered them, both Gozan, and Charrhan, and Rapheth, which are in the land of Theemath? 
\v 13 Where are the kings of Emath? And where \add is the king of\add* Arphath? And where \add is the king\add* of the city of Eppharuaim, \add and of\add* Anagugana? 
\p
\v 14 Hezekiah received the letter from the messengers, and read it, and went up to the house of the Lord, and opened it before the Lord. 
\v 15 Hezekiah prayed to the Lord, saying, 
\p
\v 16 O Lord of hosts, God of Israel, who sits upon the cherubs, you alone are the God of every kingdom of the world: you have made heaven and earth. 
\v 17 Incline your ear, O Lord, listen, O Lord; open your eyes, O Lord, look, O Lord: and behold the words of Sennacherim, which he has sent to reproach the living God. 
\v 18 For in truth, Lord, the kings of the Assyrians have laid waste the whole world, and the lands of it, 
\v 19 and have cast their idols into the fire: for they were no gods, but the work of men's hands, wood and stone; and they have cast them away. 
\v 20 But now, O Lord our God, deliver us from his hands, that every kingdom of the earth may know that you are God alone. 
\p
\v 21 Isaiah the son of Amos was sent to Hezekiah, and said to him, Thus says the Lord, the God of Israel, I have heard your prayer to me concerning Sennacherim king of the Assyrians. 
\v 22 This is the word which God has spoken concerning him; The virgin daughter of Zion has despised you, and mocked you; the daughter of Jerusalem has shaken her head at you. 
\v 23 Who have you reproached and provoked? And against whom have you lifted up your voice? And have you not lifted up your eyes on high against the Holy One of Israel? 
\v 24 For you have reproached the Lord by messengers; for you have said, With the multitude of chariots I have ascended to the height of mountains, and to the sides of Lebanon; and I have \f + \fr 37:24 \fqa Gr. \ft cut.\f*cropped the height of his cedars and the beauty of his cypresses; and I entered into the height of the forest region: 
\v 25 and I have made a bridge, and dried up the waters, and every pool of water. 
\p
\v 26 Have you not heard of these things which I did of old? I appointed \add them\add* from ancient times; but now have I manifested \add my purpose\add* of desolating nations in \add their\add* strongholds, and those who dwell in strong cities. 
\v 27 I weakened \add their\add* hands, and they withered; and they became like dry grass on the house-tops, and like grass. 
\v 28 But now I know your rest, and your going out, and your coming in. 
\v 29 Your anger with which you have been enraged, and your rancour has come up to me; therefore I will put a hook in your nose, and a bit in your lips, and will turn you back by the way by which you came. 
\p
\v 30 This will be a sign to you, Eat this year what you have sown; and the second year that which is left: and the third year sow, and reap, and plant vineyards, and eat the fruit of them. 
\v 31 Those who are left in Judea will take root downward, and bear fruit upward: 
\v 32 for out of Jerusalem there will be \f + \fr 37:32 \fqa Lit. \ft the left men.\f*a remnant, and the saved ones out of mount Zion: the zeal of the Lord of hosts will perform this. 
\v 33 Therefore thus says the Lord concerning the king of the Assyrians, He will not enter into this city, nor cast a weapon against it, nor bring a shield against it, nor make a rampart round it. 
\v 34 But by the way by which he came, by it he will return, and will not enter into this city: thus says the Lord. 
\v 35 I will protect this city to save it for my own sake, and for my servant David's sake. 
\p
\v 36 The angel of the Lord went out, and killed out of the camp of the Assyrians a hundred and eighty-five thousand: and they arose in the morning and found all \add these\add* bodies dead. 
\v 37 Sennacherim king of the Assyrians turned and departed, and dwelt in Nineveh. 
\v 38 While he was worshipping Nasarach his country's god in the house, Adramelech and Sarasar his sons struck him with swords; and they escaped into Armenia: and Asordan his son reigned in his stead. 
\c 38 
\p
\v 1 It happened at that time, \add that\add* Hezekiah was sick to the point of death. And Isaiah the prophet the son of Amos came to him, and said to him, Thus says the Lord, Give orders concerning your house: for you will die, and not live. 
\v 2 Hezekiah turned his face to the wall, and prayed to the Lord, saying, 
\v 3 Remember, O Lord, how I have walked before you in truth, with a true heart, and have done that which was pleasing in your sight. And Hezekiah wept bitterly. 
\v 4 The word of the Lord came to Isaiah, saying, Go, and say to Hezekiah, 
\v 5 Thus says the Lord, the God of David your father, I have heard your prayer, and seen your tears: behold, I \add will\add* add to your time fifteen years. 
\v 6 I will deliver you and this city out of the hand of the king of the Assyrians: and I will defend this city. 
\v 7 This \add will be\add* a sign to you from the Lord, that God will do this thing; 
\v 8 behold, I will turn back the shadow of the steps on which the sun had gone down, the ten steps of your father's house—I will turn back the sun by ten steps; so the sun went back ten steps by which the shadow had gone down. 
\d
\v 9 \sc The Prayer of Hezekiah king of Judea, when he\sc* \f + \fr 38:9 \fqa Gr. \ft was sick.\f*\sc had been sick, and was recovered from his sickness.\sc* 
\p
\v 10 I said in the end of my days, I will go to the gates of the grave: I will part with the remainder of my years. 
\v 11 I said, I will never again see the salvation of God in the land of the living: I will never again see the salvation of Israel on the earth: I will never again see man. 
\v 12 \add My life\add* has failed from among my relatives: I have parted with the remainder of my life: it has gone forth and departed from me, like one that having pitched a tent takes it down \add again\add*: my breath was with me like a weaver's web, when the one who weaves draws near to cut off \add the\add* thread. 
\v 13 In that day I was given up as to a lion until the morning: so has he broken all my bones: for thus I was given up from day \add even\add* to night. 
\v 14 As a swallow, so will I cry, and as a dove, so I mourn: for my eyes have failed with looking to the height of heaven to the Lord, who has delivered me, 
\v 15 and removed the sorrow of my soul. 
\v 16 \add Yes\add*, O Lord, for it was told you concerning this; and you have revived my breath; and I am comforted, and live. 
\v 17 For you have chosen my soul, that it should not perish: and you have cast all \add my\add* sins behind me. 
\v 18 For those who are in the grave will not praise you, neither will the dead bless you, neither will those who are in Hades hope for your mercy. 
\v 19 The living will bless you, as I also \add do\add*: for from this day I will father children, who will declare your righteousness, 
\v 20 O God of my salvation; and I will not cease blessing you with the psaltery all the days of my life before the house of God. 
\p
\v 21 Now Isaiah had said to Hezekiah; Take a cake of figs, and mash them, and apply them as a poultice, and you will be well. 
\v 22 Hezekiah said, This is a sign to Hezekiah, that I will go up to the house of God. 
\c 39 
\p
\v 1 At that time Marodach Baladan, the son of Baladan, the king of Babylonia, sent letters and ambassadors and gifts to Hezekiah: for he had heard that he \f + \fr 39:1 \fqa Gr. \ft was.\f*had been sick \add even\add* to death, and was recovered. 
\v 2 Hezekiah was glad of their coming, and he showed them the house of \add his\add* spices, and of silver, and gold, and myrrh, and incense, and ointment, and all the houses of his treasures, and all that he had in his stores: and there was nothing in his house, nor in all his dominion, which Hezekiah did not show. 
\p
\v 3 Isaiah the prophet came to king Hezekiah, and said to him, What do these men say? And where did they come to you from? And Hezekiah said, They have come to me from a land afar off, from Babylon. 
\v 4 Isaiah said, What have they seen in your house? And Hezekiah said, They have seen everything in my house; and there is nothing in my house which they have not seen: yes, also the \add possessions\add* in my treasuries. 
\v 5 Isaiah said to him, Hear the word of the Lord of hosts: 
\v 6 Behold, the days come, when they will take all the \add things that are\add* in your house, and all that your fathers have gathered until this day will go to Babylon; and they will not leave anything at all: and God has said, 
\v 7 they will also take some of your children whom you will father; and they will make them eunuchs in the house of the king of the Babylonians. 
\v 8 Hezekiah said to Isaiah, The word of the Lord which he has spoken is good: let there be, I pray, peace and righteousness in my days. 
\c 40 
\p
\v 1 Comfort, comfort my people, says God. 
\v 2 Speak, you priests, to the heart of Jerusalem; comfort her, for her humiliation is accomplished, her sin is put away: for she has received of the Lord's hand double \add the amount of\add* her sins. 
\p
\v 3 \x + \xo 40:3 \xt Mat. 3. 3; John 1. 23.\x*The voice of one crying in the wilderness, Prepare the way of the Lord, make straight the paths of our God. 
\v 4 Every valley will be filled, and every mountain and hill will be brought low: \f + \fr 40:4 \ft See \xt Luke 3. 5, \ft with which \fqa Alex. \ft agrees.\f*and all the crooked \add ways\add* will become straight, and the rough \add places\add* plains. 
\v 5 The glory of the Lord will appear, and all flesh will see the salvation of God: for the Lord has spoken \add it\add*. 
\p
\v 6 The voice of one saying, Call out; and I said, What will I call out? \x + \xo 40:6 \xt 1 Pet. 1. 24.\x*All flesh is grass, and all the glory of man like the flower of grass. 
\v 7 The grass withers, and the flower fades: 
\v 8 but the word of our God abides forever. 
\p
\v 9 O you who bring glad tidings to Zion, go up on the high mountain; lift up your voice with strength, you who bringest glad tidings to Jerusalem; lift it up, don't be afraid; say to the cities of Judah, Behold your God! 
\v 10 Behold the Lord! The Lord is coming with strength, and \add his\add* arm is with power: behold, his reward is with him, and \add his\add* work before him. 
\v 11 He will tend his flock like a shepherd, and he will gather the lambs with his arm, and will soothe those who are with young. 
\v 12 Who has measured the water in his hand, and the heaven with a span, and all the earth in a handful? Who has weighed the mountains in scales, and the forests in a balance? 
\v 13 \x + \xo 40:13 \xt Rom. 11. 34.\x*Who has known the mind of the Lord? And who has been his counsellor, to instruct him? 
\v 14 Or with whom has he taken counsel, and he has instructed him? Or who has taught him judgment, or who has taught him the way of understanding;\f + \fr 40:14 \fqa Alex. \ft + Or who has first given to him, and it shall be recompensed to him again? \xt Rom. 11. 35; \fqa Heb. \ft omits.\f* 
\v 15 since all the nations are counted as a drop from a bucket, and as the turning of a balance, \add and\add* will be counted as spittle? 
\v 16 Lebanon isn't enough to burn, nor all beasts enough for a whole-burnt offering: 
\v 17 and all the nations are as nothing, and counted as nothing. 
\p
\v 18 To whom have you compared the Lord? And with what likeness have you compared him? 
\v 19 Has not the artificer made an image, or the goldsmith having melted gold, gilt it over, \add and\add* made it a likeness? 
\v 20 For the artificer chooses out a wood that will not rot, and will wisely enquire how he will set up his image, and \add that so\add* that it should not be moved. 
\v 21 Will you not know? Will you not hear? Has it not been told you of old? Have you not known the foundations of the earth? 
\v 22 \add It is\add* he who comprehends the circle of the earth, and the inhabitants in it are like grasshoppers; he who set up the heaven as a chamber, and stretched \add it\add* out as a tent to dwell in: 
\v 23 he who appoints princes to rule as nothing, and has made the earth as nothing. 
\v 24 For they will not plant, neither will they sow, neither will their root be fixed in the ground: he has blown upon them, and they are withered, and a storm will carry them away like sticks. 
\p
\v 25 Now then to whom have you compared me, that I may be exalted? Says the Holy One. 
\v 26 Lift up your eyes on high, and see, who has displayed all these things? \add even\add* he who brings forth his host by number: he will call them all by name by \add means of his\add* great glory, and by the power of his might: nothing has escaped you. 
\p
\v 27 For don't say, O Jacob, and why have you spoken, Israel, \add saying\add*, My way is hid from God, and my God has taken away \add my\add* judgment, and has departed? 
\v 28 Now, have you not known? Have you not heard? The eternal God, the God who formed the ends of the earth, will not hunger, nor be weary, and there is no searching of his understanding. 
\v 29 He gives strength to the hungry, and sorrow to those who are not suffering. 
\v 30 For the young \add men\add* will hunger, and the youths will be weary, and the choice \add men\add* will be powerless: 
\v 31 but those who wait on God will renew \add their\add* strength; they will put forth new feathers like eagles; they will run, and not be weary; they will walk, and not hunger. 
\c 41 
\p
\v 1 Hold a feast to me, you islands: for the princes will renew \add their\add* strength: let them draw near and speak together: then let them declare judgment. 
\p
\v 2 Who raised up righteousness from the east, \add and\add* called it to his feet, so that it should go? Who will appoint \add it\add* an adversary of nations, and will dismay kings, and bury their swords in the earth, and cast forth their bows and arrows like sticks? 
\v 3 He will pursue them; the way of his feet will proceed in peace. 
\v 4 Who has worked and done these things? He has called it who called it from the generations of old; I God, \x + \xo 41:4 \xt Rev. 1. 17.\x*the first, and with respect to what is to come—I am. 
\p
\v 5 The nations saw, and feared; the ends of the earth drew near, and came together, 
\v 6 every one judging for his neighbour and \add that\add* to assist his brother: and one will say, 
\v 7 The artificer has become strong, and the coppersmith that smites with the hammer, \add and\add* also forges: sometimes he will say, It is a piece well joined: they have fastened them with nails; they will fix them, and they will not be moved. 
\p
\v 8 But you, Israel, are my servant Jacob, and he whom I have chosen, the seed of Abraham, whom I have loved: 
\v 9 whom I have taken hold of from the ends of the earth, and from its high places I have called you, and said to you, You are my servant; I have chosen you, and I have not forsaken you. 
\v 10 Don't be afraid; for I am with you: don't wander; for I am your God, who has strengthened you; and I have helped you, and have established you with my just right hand. 
\p
\v 11 Behold, all your adversaries will be ashamed and greatly agitated; for they will be as if they were not: and all your opponents will perish. 
\v 12 You will seek them, and you will not find the men who will \f + \fr 41:12 \fqa Lit. \ft transgress by wine against.\f*insolently rage against you: for they will be as if they were not, and those who war against you will not be. 
\v 13 For I am your God, who holds your right hand, who says to you, 
\v 14 Don't be afraid, Jacob, \add and you\add* Israel few in number; I have helped you, says your God, he who redeems you, O Israel. 
\v 15 Behold, I have made you like new saw-shaped threshing wheels of a waggon; and you will thresh the mountains, and beat the hills to powder, and make \add them\add* like chaff: 
\v 16 and you will winnow \add them\add*, and the wind will carry them away, and a tempest will scatter them: but you will rejoice in the holy ones of Israel. 
\p
\v 17 The poor and the needy will exult; for \add when\add* they will seek water, and there will be none, \add and\add* their tongue is parched with thirst, I the Lord God, I the God of Israel will hear, and will not forsake them: 
\v 18 but I will open rivers on the mountains, and fountains among plains: I will make the desert pools of water, and a thirsty land watercourses. 
\v 19 In the dry land I will plant the cedar and box, the myrtle and cypress, and white poplar: 
\v 20 so they may see, and know, and perceive, and understand together, that the hand of the Lord has worked these \add works\add*, and the Holy One of Israel has displayed \add them\add*. 
\p
\v 21 Your judgment draws near, says the Lord God; your counsels have drawn near, says the King of Jacob. 
\v 22 Let them draw near, and declare to you what things will come to pass; or tell \add us\add* what things were of old, and we will apply \add our\add* understanding, and we will know what are the last and the future things: 
\v 23 tell us, declare you to us the things that are coming on at the last \add time\add*, and we will know that you are gods: do good, and do evil, and we will wonder, and see at the same time 
\v 24 where you are, and where is your work: they have chosen you an abomination out of the earth. 
\p
\v 25 But I have raised up him who \add comes\add* from the north, and him who \add comes\add* from the rising of the sun: they will be called by my name: let the princes come, and like potter's clay, and like a potter treading clay, so will you be trodden down. 
\v 26 For who will declare the things from the beginning, that we may also know the former things and say that they are true? There is no one that foretells, nor any one that hears your words. 
\v 27 I will give dominion to Zion, and will comfort Jerusalem by the way. 
\v 28 For from among the nations, behold, \add there was\add* no one; and of their idols there was none to declare \add anything\add*: and if I should ask them, Where are you? They could not answer me. 
\v 29 For \add these\add* are your makers, \add as you think\add*, and those who cause you to err in vain. 
\c 42 
\p
\v 1 Jacob is \f + \fr 42:1 \ft See \xt Mat. 12. 18, \ft etc.\f*my servant, I will help him: Israel is my chosen, my soul has accepted him; I have put my Spirit upon him; he will bring forth judgment to the nations. 
\v 2 He will not cry, nor lift up \add his voice\add*, nor will his voice be heard without. 
\v 3 A bruised reed he will not break, and smoking flax will he not quench; but he will bring forth judgment to truth. 
\v 4 He will shine out, and will not be \f + \fr 42:4 \fqa Lit. \ft broken.\f*discouraged, until he has set judgment on the earth: and in his name will the nations trust. 
\p
\v 5 Thus says the Lord God, who made the heaven, and established it; who settled the earth, and the things in it, and gives breath to the people on it, and spirit to those who tread on it: 
\v 6 I the Lord God have called you in righteousness, and will hold your hand, and will strengthen you: and I have given you for the covenant of a race, for a light of the nations; 
\v 7 to open the eyes of the blind, to bring the bound and those who sit in darkness out of bonds and the prison-house. 
\p
\v 8 I am the Lord God: that is my name: I will not give my glory to another, nor my praises to graven images. 
\v 9 Behold, the ancient things have come to pass, and \add so will\add* the new things which I tell you: yes, before I tell \add them\add* they are made known to you. 
\p
\v 10 Sing a new hymn to the Lord: you \add who are\add* his dominion, glorify his name from the end of the earth: you who go down to the sea, and sail upon it; the islands, and those who dwell in them. 
\v 11 Rejoice, you wilderness, and its villages, the hamlets, and the dwellers in Kedar: the inhabitants of the rock will rejoice, they will shout from the top of the mountains. 
\v 12 They will give glory to God, \add and\add* will proclaim his praises in the islands. 
\p
\v 13 The Lord God of hosts will go forth, and crush the war: he will stir up zeal, and will shout mightily against his enemies. 
\v 14 I have been silent: will I also always be silent and forbear? I have endured like a \add woman\add* in labour: I will \add now\add* amaze and wither at once. 
\v 15 I will make desolate mountains and hills, and will dry up all their grass; and I will make the rivers islands, and dry up the pools. 
\v 16 I will bring the blind by a way that they didn't know, and I will cause them to tread paths which they have not known: I will turn darkness into light for them, and crooked things into straight. I will do these things and not forsake them. 
\v 17 But they are turned back: be completely ashamed you who trust in graven \add images\add*, who say to the molten \add images\add*, You are our gods. 
\p
\v 18 Hear, you deaf, and look up, you blind, to see. 
\v 19 Who is blind, but my servants? And deaf, but those who rule over them? Yes, the servants of God have been made blind. 
\v 20 You have often seen, and have not taken heed; \add your\add* ears have been opened, and you have not heard. 
\v 21 The Lord God has taken counsel that he might be justified, and might magnify \add his\add* praise. 
\v 22 I beheld, and the people were spoiled and plundered: for \add there is\add* a snare in the secret chambers everywhere, and in the houses also, where they have hidden them: they became a spoil, and there was no one that delivered the prey, and there was no one who said, Restore. 
\p
\v 23 Who \add is there\add* among you who will give ear to these things? Listen to the things which are coming to pass. 
\v 24 \f + \fr 42:24 \ft Some read τίς, who.\f*For what did he give Jacob up to spoil, and Israel to those who plundered him? Did not God \add do it\add* against whom they sinned? \add and\add* they would not walk in his ways, nor listen to his law. 
\v 25 So he brought upon them the fury of his wrath; and the war, and those that burnt round about them, prevailed against them; yet no one of them knew \add it\add*, neither did they lay \add it\add* to heart. 
\c 43 
\p
\v 1 Now thus says the Lord God who made you, O Jacob, and formed you, O Israel, Don't be afraid: for I have redeemed you, I have called you \add by\add* your name; you are mine. 
\v 2 If you pass through water, I am with you; and the rivers will not overflow you: and if you go through fire, you will not be burned; the flame will not burn you. 
\v 3 For I am the Lord your God, the Holy One of Israel, who saves you: I have made Egypt and Ethiopia your ransom, and \add given\add* Soene for you. 
\v 4 Since you became precious in my sight, you have become glorious, and I have loved you: and I will give men for you, and princes for \f + \fr 43:4 \fqa Gr. \ft head.\f*your life. 
\v 5 Don't be afraid; for I am with you: I will bring your seed from the east, and will gather you from the west. 
\v 6 I will say to the north, Bring; and to the south, Don't keep back; bring my sons from the \add land\add* far away, and my daughters from the ends of the earth; 
\v 7 \add even\add* all who are called by my name: for I have prepared him for my glory, and I have formed him, and have made him: 
\v 8 and I have brought forth the blind people; for \add their\add* eyes are alike blind, and those who have ears are deaf. 
\p
\v 9 All the nations are gathered together, and princes will be gathered out of them. Who will declare these things? Or who will declare to you things from the beginning? Let them bring forth their witnesses, and be justified; and let them hear, and declare the truth. 
\p
\v 10 Be my witnesses, and I \add too am\add* a witness, says the Lord God, and my servant whom I have chosen: that you may know, and believe, and understand that I am \add he\add*: before me there was no other God, and after me there will be none. 
\v 11 I am God; and beside me there is no Saviour. 
\v 12 I have declared, and have saved; I have reproached, and there was no foreign \add god\add* among you: you are my witnesses, and I am the Lord God, 
\v 13 even from the beginning; and there is no one that can deliver out of my hands: I will work, and who will turn it back? 
\p
\v 14 Thus says the Lord God who redeems you, the Holy One of Israel; For your sakes I will send to Babylon, and I will stir up all that flee, and the Chaldeans will be bound in ships. 
\v 15 I am the Lord God, your Holy One, who have appointed for Israel your king. 
\p
\v 16 Thus says the Lord, who makes a way in the sea, and a path in the mighty water; 
\v 17 who brought forth chariots and horse, and a mighty multitude: but they have \f + \fr 43:17 \fqa Or, \ft gone to sleep; See \xt Ps. 75. 5,6.\f*lain down, and will not rise: they are extinct, like quenched flax. 
\p
\v 18 Do not remember the former things, and don't consider the ancient things. 
\v 19 Behold, I \add will\add* do new things, which will presently spring forth, and you will know them: and I will make a way in the wilderness, and rivers in the dry land. 
\v 20 The beasts of the field will bless me, the owls and young ostriches; for I have given water in the wilderness, and rivers in the dry land, to give drink to my chosen race, 
\v 21 \add even\add* my people whom I have preserved to tell forth my praises. 
\p
\v 22 I have not now called you, O Jacob; neither have I made you weary, O Israel. 
\v 23 You have not brought me the sheep of your whole-burnt-offering; neither have you glorified me with your sacrifices. I have not caused you to serve with sacrifices, neither have I wearied you with frankincense. 
\v 24 Neither have you purchased for me victims for silver, neither have I desired the fat of your sacrifices: but you stood before me in your sins, and in your iniquities. 
\v 25 \f + \fr 43:25 \fqa Gr. \ft I am, I am.\f*I, \add even\add* I am he who blots out your transgressions for my own sake, and your sins; and I will not remember \add them\add*. 
\v 26 But do you remember, and let us plead \add together\add*: do you first confess your transgressions, that you may be justified. 
\v 27 Your fathers first, and your princes have transgressed against me. 
\v 28 The princes have defiled my sanctuaries: so I gave Jacob \add to enemies\add* to destroy, and Israel to reproach. 
\c 44 
\p
\v 1 But now hear, Jacob my servant; and Israel, whom I have chosen. 
\v 2 Thus says the Lord God who made you, and he who formed you from the womb; You will yet be helped: don't be afraid, my servant Jacob; and beloved Israel, whom I have chosen. 
\v 3 For I will give water to the thirsty who walk in a dry land: I will put my Spirit on your seed, and my blessings on your children: 
\v 4 and they will spring up like grass between brooks, and like willows on \add the banks of\add* running water. 
\v 5 One will say, I am God's; and another will call himself by the name of Jacob; and another will write with his hand, I am God's, and will call himself by the name of Israel. 
\p
\v 6 Thus says God the King of Israel, and the God of hosts who delivered him; \x + \xo 44:6 \xt Rev. 1. 17.\x*I am the first, and I am \f + \fr 44:6 \fqa Gr. \ft after these things\ft*the last: there is no God besides me. 
\v 7 Who is like me? Let him stand, and call, and declare, and prepare for me from the time that I made man forever; and let them tell you the things that are coming before they arrive. 
\v 8 Don't hide yourselves, nor go astray: have you not heard from the beginning, and \add haven't\add* I told you? You are witnesses if there is a God beside me. 
\p
\v 9 But those who framed \add false gods\add* did not listen then; and those who graved \add images\add* are all vain, performing their own desires, which will not profit them, but they will be ashamed 
\v 10 who form a god, and all that carve worthless things: 
\v 11 and all by whom they were made are withered: yes, let all the deaf be gathered from \add among\add* men, and let them stand together; and let them be ashamed and greatly agitated together: 
\p
\v 12 For the artificer sharpens the iron; he fashions \add the idol\add* with an axe, and fixes it with an awl, and fashions it with the strength of his arm: and he will be hungry and weak, and will drink no water. 
\v 13 The artificer having chosen a piece of wood, marks it out with a rule, and fits it with glue, and makes it like the form of a man, and like the beauty of a man, to set it up in the house. 
\v 14 He cuts wood out of the forest, which the Lord planted, \add even\add* a pine tree, and the rain made it grow, 
\v 15 that it might be for men to burn: and having taken part of it he warms himself; yes, they burn part of it, and bake loaves over it; and \add of\add* the rest they make for themselves gods, and they worship them. 
\v 16 Half of it he burns in the fire, and with half of it he bakes loaves on the coals; and having roasted flesh on it he eats, and is satisfied, and having warmed himself he says, I am comfortable, for I have warmed myself, and have seen the fire. 
\v 17 The rest he makes a graven god, and worships, and prays, saying, Deliver me; for you are my God. 
\p
\v 18 They have no understanding to perceive; for they have been blinded so that they should not see with their eyes, nor perceive with their heart. 
\v 19 One has not considered in his mind, nor known in his understanding, that he has burnt up half of it in the fire, and baked loaves on the coals of it and has roasted and eaten flesh, and of the rest of it he has made an abomination, and they worship it. 
\v 20 Know that their heart is ashes, and they err, and no one is able to deliver his soul: see, you will not say, \add There is\add* a lie in my right hand. 
\p
\v 21 Remember these things, O Jacob and Israel; for you are my servant; I have formed you \add to be\add* my servant: and you, Israel, do not forget me. 
\v 22 For behold, I have blotted out like a cloud your transgressions, and your sin like darkness: turn to me, and I will redeem you. 
\p
\v 23 Rejoice, you heavens; for God has had mercy upon Israel: sound the trumpet, you foundations of the earth: you mountains, shout \add with\add* joy, you hills, and all the trees therein: for God has redeemed Jacob, and Israel will be glorified. 
\p
\v 24 Thus says the Lord who redeems you, and who formed you from the womb, I am the Lord who performs all things: I stretched out the heaven alone, and established the earth. 
\v 25 Who else will frustrate the tokens of \f + \fr 44:25 \fqa Gr. \ft ventriloquists.\f*those who have divining spirits, and prophecies \f + \fr 44:25 \ft See \fqa Heb.\f*from the heart \add of man\add*? Turning the wise back, and making their counsel foolishness; 
\v 26 and confirming the word of his servant, and verifying the counsel of his messengers: who says to Jerusalem, You will be inhabited; and to the cities of Idumea, You will be built, and her desert places will spring forth. 
\v 27 Who says to the deep, You will be dried up, and I will dry up the rivers. 
\v 28 Who bids Cyrus be wise, and he will perform all my will: who says to Jerusalem, You will be built, and I will lay the foundation of my holy house. 
\c 45 
\p
\v 1 Thus says the Lord God to my anointed Cyrus, whose right hand I have held, that nations might be obedient before him; and I will break through the strength of kings; I will open doors before him, and cities will not be closed. 
\v 2 I will go before you, and will level mountains: I will break to pieces bronze doors, and will burst iron bars. 
\v 3 I will give you the treasures of darkness, I will open to you hidden, unseen \add treasures\add*, that you may know that I, the Lord your God, that call you by name, am the God of Israel. 
\v 4 For the sake of my servant Jacob, and Israel my elect, I will call you by your name, and accept you: but you have not known me. 
\v 5 For I am the Lord God, and there is no other God beside me; I strengthened you, and you have not known me. 
\v 6 That those who \add come\add* from the east and those who \add come\add* from the west may know that there is no God but me. I am the Lord God, and there is no one beside. 
\v 7 I am he who prepared light, and formed darkness; who makes peace, and creates evil; I am the Lord God, that does all these things. 
\p
\v 8 Let the heaven rejoice from above, and let the clouds rain righteousness: let the earth bring forth, and blossom \add with\add* mercy, and bring forth righteousness likewise: I am the Lord who created you. 
\p
\v 9 What excellent thing have I prepared like potter's clay? Will the ploughman plough the earth all day? \x + \xo 45:9 \xt Rom. 9. 20.\x*Will the clay say to the potter, What are you doing that you do not work, nor have hands? Will the thing formed answer him that formed it? 
\v 10 As though one should say to \add his\add* father, What will you father? And to his mother, What will you bring forth? 
\p
\v 11 For thus says the Lord God, the Holy One of Israel, who has formed the things that are to come, Enquire of me concerning my sons, and concerning the works of my hands: command me. 
\v 12 I have made the earth, and a man upon it: I with my hand have established the heaven; I have commanded all the stars. 
\v 13 I have raised him up \add to be\add* a king with righteousness, and all his ways are right: he will build my city, and will turn the captivity of my people, not \f + \fr 45:13 \fqa Gr. \ft with.\f*for ransoms, nor for rewards, says the Lord of hosts. 
\p
\v 14 Thus says the Lord of hosts, Egypt has laboured \add for you\add*; and the merchandise of the Ethiopians, and the Sabeans, men of stature, will pass over to you, and they will be your servants; and they will follow after you bound in fetters, and will pass over to you, and will do obeisance to you, and make supplication to you: because God is in you; and there is no God beside you, \add O Lord\add*. 
\v 15 For you are God, yet we didn't know \add it\add*, the God of Israel, the Saviour. 
\v 16 All that are opposed to him will be ashamed and greatly agitated, and will walk in shame: you isles, \f + \fr 45:16 \ft See chap \xt 41. 1.\f*keep a feast to me. 
\v 17 Israel is saved by the Lord with an everlasting salvation: they will not be ashamed nor greatly agitated for evermore. 
\p
\v 18 Thus says the Lord that made the heaven, this God who \f + \fr 45:18 \fqa Gr. \ft showed.\f*created the earth, and made it; he marked it out, he didn't make it in vain, but formed it to be inhabited: I am the Lord, and there is no one beside. 
\v 19 I have not spoken in secret, nor in a dark place of the earth: I said not to the seed of Jacob, Seek vanity: \f + \fr 45:19 \fqa Gr. \ft I am, I am.\f*I, even I, am the Lord, speaking righteousness, and proclaiming truth. 
\p
\v 20 Assemble yourselves and come; take counsel together, you who escape from the nations: those who set up wood, \add even\add* their graven image, have no knowledge, nor they who pray to gods that do not save. 
\v 21 If they will declare, let them draw near, so they may know together, who has caused these things to be heard from the beginning: then it was told you. I am God, and there isn't another beside me; a just \add God\add* and a Saviour; there is no one but me. 
\v 22 Turn to me, and you will be saved, you who \add come\add* from the end of the earth: I am God, and there is no one other. 
\v 23 By myself \x + \xo 45:23 \xt Rom. 14. 11.\x*I swear, righteousness will surely proceed out of my mouth; my words will not be frustrated; that to me \x + \xo 45:23 \xt Phil. 2:10--11\x*every knee will bend, and every tongue will swear by God, 
\v 24 saying, Righteousness and glory will come to him: and all that remove them from their borders will be ashamed. 
\v 25 By the Lord they will be justified, and in God will all the seed of the children of Israel be glorified. 
\c 46 
\p
\v 1 Bel has fallen, Nabo is broken to pieces, their graven images have gone to the wild beasts and the cattle: you take them packed up as a burden to the weary, exhausted, hungry, and helpless man; 
\v 2 who will not be able to save themselves from war, but they themselves are led \add away\add* captive. 
\p
\v 3 Hear me, O house of Jacob, and all the remnant of Israel, who were borne \add by me\add* from the womb, and taught \add by me\add* from infancy, \add even\add* to old age: 
\v 4 I am \add he\add*; and until you will have grown old, I am \add he\add*: I bear you, I have made, and I will \f + \fr 46:4 \fqa Or, \ft put up with.\f*relieve, I will take up and save you. 
\p
\v 5 To whom have you compared me? See, consider, you who go astray. 
\v 6 Those who furnish gold out of a purse, and silver by weight, will weigh it in a scale, and they hire a goldsmith and make \f + \fr 46:6 \fqa Gr. \ft things made with hands.\f*idols, and bow down, and worship them. 
\v 7 They bear it on the shoulder, and go; and if they put it on its place, it remains, it cannot move: and whoever will cry to it, it cannot hear; it cannot save him from trouble. 
\p
\v 8 Remember these things, and groan: repent, you who have gone astray, return in your heart; 
\v 9 and remember the former things \add that were\add* of old: for I am God, and there is no one other beside me, 
\v 10 telling beforehand the latter events before they come to pass, and they are accomplished together: and I said, All my counsel will stand, and I will do all things that I have planned: 
\v 11 calling a bird from the east, and from a land far off, for the things which I have planned: I have spoken, and brought \add him\add*; I have created and made \add him\add*; I have brought him, and prospered his way. 
\p
\v 12 Listen to me, you senseless ones, that are far from righteousness: 
\v 13 I have brought near my righteousness, and I will not be slow with the salvation that is from me: I have given salvation in Zion to Israel for glory. 
\c 47 
\p
\v 1 Come down, sit on the ground, O virgin daughter of Babylon: sit on the ground, O daughter of the Chaldeans: for you will no more be called tender and luxurious. 
\v 2 Take a millstone, grind meal: remove your veil, uncover your white hairs, make bare the leg, pass through the rivers. 
\v 3 Your shame will be uncovered, your reproaches will be brought to light: I will exact due vengeance from you, I will no longer deliver you to men. 
\p
\v 4 Your deliverer is the Lord of hosts, the Holy One of Israel is his name. 
\p
\v 5 Sit down, pierced with woe; go into darkness, O daughter of the Chaldeans: you will no more be called the strength of a kingdom. 
\v 6 I have been provoked with my people; you have defiled my inheritance: I gave them into your hand, but you did not extend mercy to them: you made the yoke of the aged man very heavy, 
\v 7 and said, I will be a princess forever: you did not perceive these things in your heart, nor did you remember the latter end. 
\p
\v 8 But now hear these words, you luxurious one, \add you who are\add* the one who sits \add at ease\add*, who is secure, who says in her heart, I am, and there isn't another; I will not sit a widow, neither I will know bereavement. 
\v 9 But now these two things will come upon you suddenly in one day, the loss of children and widowhood will come suddenly upon you, for your sorcery, for the strength of your enchantments, 
\v 10 for your \f + \fr 47:10 \fqa Gr. \ft the hope of thy wickedness.\f*trusting in wickedness: for you said, I am, and there isn't another: know, the understanding of these things and your harlotry will be your shame; for you said in your heart, I am, and there isn't another. 
\p
\v 11 Destruction will come upon you, and you will not be aware; \add there will be\add* a pit, and you will fall into it: and grief will come upon you, and you will not be able to be \f + \fr 47:11 \fqa Or, \ft pure.\f*clear; and destruction will come suddenly upon you, and you will not know. 
\v 12 Stand now with your enchantments, and with the abundance of your sorcery, which you have learned from your youth; if you can be profited. 
\v 13 You are wearied in your counsels. Let the astrologers of the heaven now stand and deliver you, let those who see the stars tell you what is about to come upon you. 
\v 14 Behold, they will all be burnt up as sticks in the fire; they will surely not deliver their life from the flame. Because you have coals of fire, sit on them; 
\v 15 these will be your help. You have wearied yourself with traffic from your youth: every man has wandered to his own home, but you will have no deliverance. 
\c 48 
\p
\v 1 Hear these \add words\add*, you house of Jacob, who are called by the name of Israel, and have come forth out of Judah, who swear by the name of the Lord God of Israel, making mention \add of it, but\add* not with truth, nor with righteousness; 
\v 2 maintaining also the name of the holy city, and staying themselves on the God of Israel: the Lord of hosts is his name. The former things I have already declared; 
\v 3 and they have proceeded out of my mouth, and it became well known; I worked suddenly, and \add the events\add* came to pass. 
\p
\v 4 I know that you are stubborn, and your neck is an iron sinew, and your forehead bronze. 
\v 5 I told you \f + \fr 48:5 \fqa Alex. \ft the ancient things before they came.\f*of old what \add should be\add* before it came upon you; I made it known to you, lest you should say, \add My\add* idols have done \add it\add* for me; and should say, \add My\add* graven and molten images have commanded me. 
\v 6 You have heard all this, but you have not known: yet I have made \f + \fr 48:6 \fqa Or, \ft audible.\f*known to you the new things from now on, which are coming to pass, and you didn't say, 
\v 7 Now they come to pass, and not formerly: and you didn't hear of them in former days: don't say, Yes, I know them. 
\v 8 You have neither known, nor understood, neither from the beginning have I opened your ears: for I knew that you would surely deal treacherously, and would be called a transgressor even from the womb. 
\p
\v 9 For my own sake will I show you my wrath, and will bring before you my glorious acts, that I may not completely destroy you. 
\v 10 Behold, I have sold you, \add but\add* not for silver; but I have rescued you from the furnace of affliction. 
\v 11 For my own sake I will do \add this\add* for you, because my name is profaned; and I will not give my glory to another. 
\p
\v 12 Hear me, O Jacob, and Israel whom I call; I am the first, and I \f + \fr 48:12 \fqa Gr. \ft am.\f*endure forever. 
\v 13 My hand also has founded the earth, and my right hand has fixed the sky: I will call them, and they will stand together. 
\v 14 All will be gathered, and will hear: who has told them these things? Out of love to you I have fulfilled your desire on Babylon, to abolish the seed of the Chaldeans. 
\v 15 I have spoken, I have called, I have brought him, and made his way prosperous. 
\p
\v 16 Draw near to me, and hear these words; I have not spoken in secret from the beginning: when it took place, there I was, and now the Lord, \add even\add* the Lord, and his Spirit, has sent me. 
\v 17 Thus says the Lord that delivered you, the Holy One of Israel; I am your God, I have shown you how you should find the way in which you should walk. 
\v 18 If you had listened to my commandments, \add then\add* your peace would have been like a river, and your righteousness like a wave of the sea. 
\v 19 Your seed also would have been like the sand, and your offspring like the dust of the ground: yet even now you will surely not be completely destroyed, neither will your name perish before me. 
\p
\v 20 Go forth from Babylon, you who flee from the Chaldeans: utter aloud a voice of joy, and let this be made known, proclaim it to the end of the earth; say, The Lord has delivered his servant Jacob. 
\v 21 If they thirst, he will lead them through the desert; he will bring water for them out of the rock: the rock will be cloven, and the water will flow forth, and my people will drink. 
\v 22 There is no joy, says the Lord, to the ungodly. 
\c 49 
\p
\v 1 Listen to me, you islands; and pay attention, you nations; after a long time it will come to pass, says the Lord: from my mother's womb he has called my name: 
\v 2 and he has made my mouth like a sharp sword, and he has hidden me under the shadow of his hand; he has made me like a choice shaft, and he has hidden me in his quiver; 
\v 3 and said to me, You are my servant, O Israel, and in you I will be glorified. 
\v 4 Then I said, I have laboured in vain, I have given my strength for vanity and for nothing: therefore my judgment is with the Lord, and my labour before my God. 
\v 5 Now, thus says the Lord who formed me from the womb to be his own servant, to gather Jacob to him and Israel. I will be gathered and glorified before the Lord, and my God will be my strength. 
\v 6 He said to me, \add It is\add* a great thing for you to be called my servant, to establish the tribes of Jacob, and to recover the dispersion of Israel: behold, \x + \xo 49:6 \xt Acts 13. 47.\x*I have given you for the \f + \fr 49:6 \fqa Gr. \ft a perpetual covenant.\f*covenant of a race, for a light of the nations, that you should be for salvation to the end of the earth. 
\p
\v 7 Thus says the Lord who delivered you, the God of Israel, Sanctify him who despises his life, him who is abhorred by the nations that are the servants of princes: kings will behold him, and princes will arise, and will worship him, for the Lord's sake: for the Holy One of Israel is faithful, and I have chosen you. 
\p
\v 8 Thus says the Lord, \x + \xo 49:8 \xt 2 Cor. 6. 2.\x*In an acceptable time have I heard you, and in a day of salvation have I succoured you: and I have formed you, and given you for a covenant of the nations, to establish the earth, and to cause to inherit the desert heritages: 
\v 9 saying to those who are in bonds, Go forth; and \add bidding\add* those who are in darkness show themselves. They will be fed in all the streets, and in all the paths \add will be\add* their pasture. 
\v 10 \x + \xo 49:10 \xt Rev. 7. 16.\x*They will not hunger, neither will they thirst; neither will the heat nor the sun strike them; but he who has mercy on them will comfort \add them\add*, and by fountains of waters he will lead them. 
\v 11 I will make every mountain a road, and every path a pasture to them. 
\v 12 Behold, these will come from far: \add and\add* these from the north and the west, and others from the land of the Persians. 
\p
\v 13 Rejoice, you heavens; and let the earth be glad: let the mountains break forth \add with\add* joy; for the Lord has had mercy on his people, and has comforted the lowly ones of his people. 
\p
\v 14 But Zion said, The Lord has forsaken me, and, The Lord has forgotten me. 
\v 15 Will a woman forget her child, so as not to have compassion upon the offspring of her womb? But if a woman should even forget these, yet I will not forget you, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 16 Behold, I have painted your walls on my hands, and you are continually before me. 
\v 17 You will soon be built by those by whom you were destroyed, and those who made you desolate will go forth from you. 
\p
\v 18 Lift up your eyes round about, and look on them all; behold, they are gathered together, and have come to you. \add As\add* I live, says the Lord, you will clothe yourself with them all as with an ornament, and put them on as a bride her attire. 
\v 19 For your desert and marred and ruined \add places\add* will now be too narrow because of the inhabitants, and those who devoured you will be removed far from you. 
\v 20 For your sons whom you have lost will say in your ears, The place \add is too\add* narrow for me: make room for me that I may dwell. 
\v 21 You will say in your heart, Who has fathered these for me? Because I \add was\add* childless, and a widow; but who has brought these up for me? And I was left alone; but where did these come to me from? 
\p
\v 22 Thus says the Lord, \add even\add* the Lord, Behold, I lift up my hand to the nations, and I will lift up my signal to the islands: and they will bring your sons in \add their\add* bosom, and will bear your daughters on \add their\add* shoulders. 
\v 23 Kings will be your wet-nurses, and their princesses your carers, they will bow down to you on the face of the earth, and will lick the dust of your feet; and you will know that I am the Lord, and those who wait on me will not be shamed. 
\p
\v 24 Will any one take spoils from a giant? And if one should take \add a man\add* captive unjustly, will he be delivered? 
\v 25 For thus says the Lord, If one should take a giant captive, he will take spoils, and he who takes \add them\add* from a mighty \add man\add* will be delivered: for I will plead your cause, and I will deliver your children. 
\v 26 Those who afflicted you will eat their own flesh; and they will drink their own blood like new wine, and will be drunk: and all flesh will perceive that I am the Lord who delivers you, and that upholds the strength of Jacob. 
\c 50 
\p
\v 1 Thus says the Lord, Of what kind is your mother's bill of divorce by which I put her away? Or to which debtor have I sold you? Behold, you are sold for your sins, and for your iniquities I have put your mother away. 
\v 2 Why did I come, and there was no man? \add why\add* did I call, and there was none to listen? Isn't my hand strong to redeem? Or can I not deliver? Behold, by my rebuke I will dry up the sea, and make rivers a wilderness; and their fish will be dried up because there is no water, and will die for thirst. 
\v 3 I will clothe the sky with darkness, and will make its covering like sackcloth. 
\p
\v 4 \f + \fr 50:4 \fqa Gr. \ft the Lord the Lord. See on \xt 3 Kings 8. 53.\f*The Lord \add even\add* God gives me the tongue of instruction, to know when it is fit to speak a word: he has appointed for me early, he has given me an ear to hear: 
\v 5 and the instruction of the Lord, even the Lord, opens my ears, and I do not disobey, nor dispute. 
\v 6 I gave my back to scourges, and my cheeks to blows; and I didn't turn away my face from the shame of spitting: 
\v 7 but the Lord God became my helper; therefore I was not ashamed, but I set my face like a solid rock; and I know that I will never be ashamed, 
\v 8 for he who has justified me draws near; who is he who pleads with me? Let him stand up against me at the same time: yes, who is he who pleads with me? Let him draw near to me. 
\v 9 Behold, the Lord, the Lord, will help me; who will hurt me? Behold, all you will grow old like a garment, and a moth will devour you. 
\p
\v 10 Who is among you who fears the Lord? Let him listen to the voice of his servant: you who walk in darkness, and have no light, trust in the name of the Lord, and rely on God. 
\v 11 Behold, you all kindle a fire, and feed a flame: walk in the light of your fire, and in the flame which you have kindled. This has happened to you for my sake; you will lie down in sorrow. 
\c 51 
\p
\v 1 Listen to me, you who follow after righteousness, and seek the Lord: look to the solid rock, which you have hewn, and to the hole of the pit which you have dug. 
\v 2 Look to Abraham your father, and to Sarrha who bore you: for he was alone when I called him, and blessed him, and loved him, and multiplied him. 
\v 3 Now I will comfort you, O Zion: and I have comforted all her desolate places; and I will make her desolate places like the garden of the Lord; gladness and exultation will be found in her, thanksgiving and the voice of praise. 
\p
\v 4 Hear me, hear me, my people; and you kings, listen to me: for a law will proceed from me, and my judgment \add will be\add* as a light for \f + \fr 51:4 \fqa Or, \ft the Gentiles.\f*the nations. 
\v 5 My righteousness speedily draws near, and my salvation will go forth \f + \fr 51:5 \ft Not in \fqa Heb. \ft or \fqa Alex.\f*as light, and on my arm will the nations trust: the isles will wait for me, and on my arm will they trust. 
\v 6 Lift up your eyes to the sky, and look on the earth beneath: for the sky was darkened like smoke, and the earth will grow old like a garment, and the inhabitants will die in the same way: but my righteousness will not fail. 
\p
\v 7 Hear me, you who know judgment, the people in whose heart is my law: don't fear the reproach of men, and don't be overcome by their contempt. 
\v 8 For as a garment will be devoured by time, and as wool will be devoured by a moth, \add so they will be consumed\add*; but my righteousness will be forever, and my salvation for all generations. 
\p
\v 9 Awake, awake, O Jerusalem, and put on the strength of your arm; awake as \f + \fr 51:9 \fqa Gr. \ft the beginning of day.\f*in the early time, as the ancient generation. 
\v 10 Are you not the one who dried the sea, the waters of the great deep; who made the depths of the sea a way of passage for those being delivered? 
\v 11 for by \add the help of\add* the Lord they will return, and come to Zion with joy and everlasting exultation, for praise and joy will come upon their head: pain, and grief, and groaning, have fled away. 
\p
\v 12 I, \add even\add* I, am he who comforts you: consider who you are, that you were afraid of mortal man, and of the son of man, who are withered like grass. 
\v 13 You have forgotten God who made you, who made the sky and founded the earth; and you were continually afraid because of the wrath of him who afflicted you: for \add because\add* he counselled to take you away, yet now where is the wrath of him who afflicted you? 
\v 14 For in your deliverance he will not halt, nor tarry; 
\v 15 for I am your God, who troubles the sea, and causes its waves to roar: the Lord of hosts is my name. 
\v 16 I will put my words into your mouth, and I will shelter you under the shadow of my hand, with which I fixed the sky, and founded the earth: and \add the Lord\add* will say to Zion, You are my people. 
\p
\v 17 Awake, awake, stand up, O Jerusalem, you who have drunk from the hand of the Lord the cup of his fury: for you have drunk out and drained the cup of calamity, the cup of wrath: 
\v 18 and there was none to comfort you of all the children whom you bore; and there was none to take hold of your hand, not even of all the children whom you have reared. 
\v 19 Therefore these things are against you; who will sympathise with you in your grief? Downfall, and destruction, famine, and sword: who will comfort you? 
\v 20 Your sons are perplexed, who sleep at the top of every street like a half-boiled beet; those who are full of the anger of the Lord, caused to faint by the Lord God. 
\p
\v 21 Therefore hear, you who are afflicted and drunk, \add but\add* not with wine; 
\v 22 thus says the Lord God who judges his people, Behold, I have taken out of your hand the cup of calamity, the cup of my wrath; and you will not drink it any more. 
\v 23 I will give it into the hands of those who injured you, and those who afflicted you; who said to your soul, Bow down, that we may pass over: and you made your back level with the ground for those passing by. 
\c 52 
\p
\v 1 Awake, awake, Zion; put on your strength, O Zion; and put on your glory, Jerusalem the holy city: the uncircumcised and unclean will not pass through you any more. 
\v 2 Shake off the dust and arise; sit down, Jerusalem: take off the band of your neck, captive daughter of Zion. 
\p
\v 3 For thus says the Lord, You have been sold for nothing; and you will not be ransomed with silver. 
\v 4 Thus says the Lord, My people went down before to Egypt to sojourn there; and were carried away forcibly to the Assyrians. 
\v 5 Now why are you here? Thus says the Lord, Because my people was taken for nothing, wonder and howl. Thus says the Lord, On account of you \x + \xo 52:5 \xt Rom. 2. 24.\x*my name is continually blasphemed among the nations. 
\v 6 Therefore my people will know my name in that day, for I am he who speaks: I am present, 
\v 7 as \f + \fr 52:7 \xt Rom. 10. 15. \ft Another reading is 'How beautiful are the feet,' etc. \fqa Lit. \ft Why have the feet been made beautiful? See also \xt Joel 2. 2.,\ft 'the morning [spread] upon the mountains.'\f*a season of beauty upon the mountains, as the feet of one preaching glad tidings of peace, as one preaching good news: for I will publish your salvation, saying, O Zion, your God will reign. 
\v 8 For the voice of those who guard you is exalted, and with the voice together they will rejoice: for eyes will look to eyes, when the Lord will have mercy upon Zion. 
\v 9 Let the waste places of Jerusalem break forth \add in\add* joy together, because the Lord has had mercy upon her, and has delivered Jerusalem. 
\v 10 The Lord will reveal his holy arm in the sight of all the nations; and all the ends of the earth will see the salvation that \add comes\add* from our God. 
\p
\v 11 \x + \xo 52:11 \xt 2 Cor. 6. 17,18.\x*Depart, depart, go out from from there, and touch no unclean thing; go out from the midst of her; separate yourselves, you who bear the vessels of the Lord. 
\v 12 For you will not go forth with tumult, neither go by flight: for the Lord will go first in advance of you; and the God of Israel will be he who \f + \fr 52:12 \fqa Gr. \ft gathers you.\f*brings up your rear. 
\p
\v 13 Behold, my servant will understand, and be exalted, and glorified exceedingly. 
\v 14 As many will be amazed at you, so will your face be without glory from men, and your glory \add will not be honoured\add* by the sons of men. 
\v 15 Thus will many nations wonder at him; and kings will keep their mouths shut: \x + \xo 52:15 \xt Rom. 15. 21.\x*for they to whom no report was brought concerning him, will see; and they who have not heard, will consider. 
\c 53 
\p
\v 1 O Lord, \x + \xo 53:1 \xt John 12. 38; Rom. 10. 16.\x*who has believed our report? And to whom has the arm of the Lord been revealed? 
\v 2 We brought a report as \add of\add* a child before him; \add he is\add* like a root in a thirsty land: he has no form nor comeliness; and we saw him, but he had no form nor beauty. 
\v 3 But his form was ignoble, and inferior to that of the children of men; \add he was\add* a man in suffering, and acquainted with the bearing of sickness, for his face is turned from \add us\add*: he was dishonoured, and not esteemed. 
\v 4 \x + \xo 53:4 \xt Mat. 8. 17.\x*He bears our sins, and is pained for us: yet we accounted him to be in trouble, and in suffering, and in affliction. 
\v 5 But he was wounded on account of our sins, and was \f + \fr 53:5 \fqa Or, \ft made sick.\f*bruised because of our iniquities: the chastisement of our peace was upon him; \add and\add* by his \f + \fr 53:5 \fqa Gr. \ft bruise. \xt 1 Pet. 2. 22.\f*bruises we were healed. 
\v 6 All we like sheep have gone astray; every one has gone astray to his own way; and the Lord gave him up for our sins. 
\p
\v 7 He, because of his affliction, opens not his mouth: \x + \xo 53:7 \xt Acts 8. 32,33.\x*he was led as a sheep to the slaughter, and as a lamb before the shearer is silent, so he opens not his mouth. 
\v 8 In \add his\add* humiliation his judgment was taken away: who will declare his generation? For his life is taken away from the earth: because of the iniquities of my people he was led to death. 
\v 9 I will give the wicked for his burial, and the rich for his death; \x + \xo 53:9 \xt 1 Pet. 2. 22.\x*for he practised no wickedness, nor deceit with his mouth. 
\v 10 The Lord also wills to purge him from the affliction. If you make an offering for sin, your soul will see a long-lived seed: 
\v 11 the Lord also wills to take away from the pain of his soul, to show him light, and to form \add him\add* with understanding; to justify a \f + \ft `justify' and `righteous' are verb and adjective forms of the same Greek word, but are usally translated using different English words as here.\f*righteous one who serves many well; and he himself will bear their sins. 
\v 12 Therefore he will inherit many, and he will divide the spoils of the mighty; because his soul was delivered to death: and \x + \xo 53:12 \xt Mark 15. 28.\x*he was numbered among the transgressors; and he bore the sins of many, and was delivered because of their iniquities. 
\c 54 
\p
\v 1 \x + \xo 54:1 \xt Gal. 4. 27.\x*Rejoice, barren woman who has not given birth; break forth and cry, you who are not in labour: for the children of the desolate are more than those of her who has a husband: for the Lord has said, 
\v 2 Enlarge the place of your tent, and of your curtains: fix \add the tent-pegs\add*, don't hold back, lengthen your cords, and strengthen your tent-pegs; 
\v 3 spread forth \add your tent\add* yet to the right and the left: for your seed will inherit the nations, and you will make the desolate cities to be inhabited. 
\v 4 Don't be afraid, because you have been put to shame, neither be greatly agitated, because you were reproached: for you will forget your \f + \fr 54:4 \fqa Gr. \ft ancient \fqa Or, \ft everlasting.\f*former shame, and will surely not remember the reproach of your widowhood. 
\v 5 For \add it is\add* the Lord who made you; the Lord of hosts is his name: and he who delivered you, he is the God of Israel, \add and\add* will be called \add so\add* by the whole earth. 
\v 6 The Lord has not called you as a deserted and faint-hearted woman, nor as a woman hated from \add her\add* youth, says your God. 
\p
\v 7 For a little while I left you: but with great mercy will I have compassion upon you. 
\v 8 In a little wrath I turned away my face from you; but with everlasting mercy will I have compassion upon you, says the Lord who delivers you. 
\p
\v 9 From the time of the water of Noah this is my \add purpose\add*: like I swore to him at that time, \add saying\add* of the earth, I will no more be angry with you, neither when you are threatened, 
\v 10 will the mountains depart, nor will your hills be removed: so neither will my mercy fail you, and the covenant of your peace will surely not be removed: for \f + \fr 54:10 \fqa Alex. \ft κύριος for κύριε adopted here. Compare \xt Mat. 16. 22, \ft with this passage.\f*the Lord \add who is\add* gracious to you has spoken \add it\add*. 
\p
\v 11 Afflicted and outcast you have not been comforted: behold, I \add will\add* prepare carbuncle \add for\add* your stones, and sapphire for your foundations; 
\v 12 and I will make your buttresses jasper, and your gates crystal, and your border precious stones. 
\v 13 \x + \xo 54:13 \xt John 6. 45.\x*And \add I will cause\add* all your sons \add to be\add* taught by God, and your children \add to be\add* in great peace. 
\v 14 You will be built in righteousness: abstain from injustice, and you will not fear; and trembling will not come near you. 
\v 15 Behold, strangers will come to you by me, and will sojourn with you, and will run to you for refuge. 
\p
\v 16 Behold, I have created you, not like the coppersmith blowing coals, and bringing out a vessel \add fit\add* for work; but I have created you, not for ruin, that \add I\add* should destroy \add you\add*. 
\v 17 I will not suffer any \f + \fr 54:17 \fqa Gr. \ft instrument.\f*weapon formed against you to prosper; and every voice that will rise up against you for judgment, you will vanquish them all; and your adversaries will be \add condemned\add* thereby. There is an inheritance to those who serve the Lord, and you will be righteous before me, says the Lord. 
\c 55 
\p
\v 1 You who thirst, go to the water, and all that have no money, go \add and\add* buy; and eat \add and drink\add* wine and fat without money or price. 
\v 2 Why do you spend money on what is not satisfying, or your labour \f + \fr 55:2 \ft See \xt Col. 2. \ft ult.\f*for what does not fill? Listen to me, and you will eat that which is good, and your soul will delight in good things. 
\p
\v 3 Give heed with your ears, and follow my ways: listen to me, and your soul will live in prosperity; and I will make with you an everlasting covenant, \x + \xo 55:3 \xt Acts 13. 34.\x*the sure mercies of David. 
\v 4 Behold, I have made him a testimony among the nations, a prince and commander to the nations. 
\v 5 Nations which don't know you, will call upon you, and peoples which are not acquainted with you, will flee to you for refuge, for the sake of the Lord your God, the Holy One of Israel; for he has glorified you. 
\p
\v 6 Seek you the Lord, and when you find him, call upon him; and when he will draw near to you, 
\v 7 let the ungodly leave his ways, and the transgressor his counsels: and let him return to the Lord, and he will find mercy; for he will abundantly pardon your sins. 
\v 8 For my counsels are not like your counsels, nor are my ways like your ways, says the Lord. 
\v 9 But as the heaven is distant from the earth, so is my way distant from your ways, and your thoughts from my mind. 
\v 10 For as rain will come down, or snow, from heaven, and will not return until it has soaked the earth, and it brings forth, and sprouts, and \x + \xo 55:10 \xt 2 Cor. 9. 10.\x*gives seed to the sower, and bread for food: 
\v 11 so will my word be, whatever will proceed out of my mouth, it will by no means turn back, until all the things which I willed will have been accomplished; and I will make your ways prosperous, and \add will effect\add* my commands. 
\v 12 For you will go forth with joy, and will be taught with gladness: for the mountains and the hills will exult to welcome you with joy, and all the trees of the field will applaud with their branches. 
\v 13 Instead of the bramble will come up the cypress, and instead of the nettle will come up the myrtle: and the Lord will be a name and an everlasting sign, and will not fail. 
\c 56 
\p
\v 1 Thus says the Lord, Keep judgment, and do justice: for my salvation is near to come, and my mercy to be revealed. 
\v 2 Blessed is the man who does these things, and the man who holds by them, and keeps the sabbaths from profaning them, and keeps his hands from doing unrighteousness. 
\p
\v 3 Don't let the stranger who attaches himself to the Lord say, Surely the Lord will separate me from his people: and don't let the eunuch say, I am a dry tree. 
\v 4 Thus says the Lord to the eunuchs, as many as will keep my sabbaths, and choose the things which I take pleasure in, and take hold of my covenant; 
\v 5 I will give to them in my house and within my walls a honourable place, better than sons and daughters: I will give them an everlasting name, and it will not fail. 
\v 6 And \add I will give it\add* to the strangers that attach themselves to the Lord, to serve him, and to love the name of the Lord, to be to him servants and handmaids; and \add as for\add* all that keep my sabbaths from profaning \add them\add*, and that take hold of my covenant; 
\v 7 I will bring them to my holy mountain, and gladden them in my house of prayer: their whole-burnt-offerings and their sacrifices will be acceptable upon my altar; for \x + \xo 56:7 \xt Mat. 21. 13.\x*my house will be called a house of prayer for all nations, 
\v 8 says the Lord who gathers the dispersed of Israel; for I will gather to him a congregation. 
\p
\v 9 All you beasts of the field, come; devour, all you beasts of the forest. 
\v 10 See how they are all blinded: they have not known; \add they are\add* dumb dogs \add that\add* will not bark; dreaming of rest, loving to slumber. 
\v 11 Yes, they are insatiable dogs, that don't know what it is to be filled, and they are wicked, having no understanding: all have followed their own ways, each according to his own \add will\add*. 
\c 57 
\p
\v 1 See how the just man has perished, and no one lays \add it\add* to heart: and righteous men are taken away, and no one considers: for the righteous has been removed out of the way of injustice. 
\v 2 His burial will be in peace: he has been removed out of the way. 
\p
\v 3 But draw near here, you lawless children, the seed of adulterers and the prostitute. 
\v 4 How have you been rioting? And against whom have you opened your mouth, and against whom have you loosened your tongue? Are you not children of perdition? A lawless seed? 
\v 5 who call upon idols under the leafy trees, killing \f + \fr 57:5 \fqa Gr. \ft their.\f*your children in the valleys among the rocks? 
\v 6 That is your portion, this is your lot: and to them have you poured forth drink-offerings, and to these have you offered food-offerings. Will I not therefore be angry for these things? 
\p
\v 7 On a lofty and high mountain, there is your bed, and there you carried up your food-offerings: 
\v 8 and behind the posts of your door you placed your memorials. Did you think that if you should depart from me, you would gain? You have loved those that lay with you; 
\v 9 and you have multiplied your prostitution with them, and you have increased the number of those who are far from you, and have sent ambassadors beyond your borders, and have been debased even to hades. 
\v 10 You have wearied yourself with your many ways; yet you didn't say, I will cease to strengthen myself: for you have done these things; therefore you have not supplicated me. 
\p
\v 11 Through dread of whom have you feared, and lied against me, and have not remembered, nor \f + \fr 57:11 \fqa Gr. \ft taken me into your mind, nor into your heart.\f*considered me, nor regarded me, yes, though when I see you I pass you by, yet you have not feared me. 
\p
\v 12 I will declare your righteousness, and your sins, which will not profit you. 
\v 13 When you cry out, let them deliver you in your affliction: for all these the wind will take, and the tempest will carry \add them\add* away: but those who cling to me will possess the land, and will inherit my holy mountain. 
\v 14 They will say, \f + \fr 57:14 \fqa Lit. \ft purge.\f*Clear the ways before him, and take up the stumbling-blocks out of the way of my people. 
\p
\v 15 Thus says the Most High, who dwells on high forever, \f + \fr 57:15 \fqa Or, \ft Most Holy.\f*Holy in the holies, is his name, the Most High resting in the holies, and giving patience to the faint-hearted, and giving life to the broken-hearted: 
\v 16 I will not take vengeance on you forever, neither will I be always angry with you: for my Spirit will go forth from me, and I have created all breath. 
\v 17 On account of sin for a little while I grieved him, and struck him, and turned away my face from him; and he was grieved, and he went on sorrowful in his ways. 
\v 18 I have seen his ways, and healed him, and comforted him, and given him true comfort; 
\v 19 peace upon peace to those who are far off, and to those who are near: and the Lord has said, I will heal them. 
\p
\v 20 But the unrighteous will be tossed like troubled waves, and will not be able to rest. 
\v 21 There is no \f + \fr 57:21 \ft See chap \xt 48. 22.\f*joy to the ungodly, said God. 
\c 58 
\p
\v 1 Cry out loudly, and don't hold back; lift up your voice as with a trumpet, and declare to my people their sins, and to the house of Jacob their iniquities. 
\v 2 They seek me day by day, and desire to know my ways, as a people that had done righteousness, and had not forsaken the judgment of their God: they now ask of me righteous judgment, and desire to draw near to God, 
\v 3 saying, Why have we fasted, and you don't regard? \add Why\add* have we afflicted our souls, and you did not know it? 
\p No, in the days of your fasts you find your pleasures, and you wound all those who are under your power. 
\v 4 If you fast for quarrels and strifes, and strike the lowly with \add your\add* fists, why do you fast to me as \add you do\add* this day, so that your voice may be heard in crying? 
\v 5 Is this the fast I have chosen, a day for a man to humble his soul? Even if you should bow your neck like a hook, and spread sackcloth and ashes under you, not even then will you call it an acceptable fast. 
\v 6 Is not this the fast I have chosen, says the Lord: rather loose every burden of wickedness, untie the knots of hard bargains, set the bruised free, and cancel every unjust account. 
\v 7 Break your bread for the hungry, and bring the homeless poor into your house: if you see someone naked, clothe \add him\add*, and do not ignore those of your own kin.
\p
\v 8 Then your light will break forth like the morning, and your health will speedily spring forth: and your righteousness will go before you, and the glory of God will compass you. 
\v 9 Then you will cry, and God will listen to you; while you are still speaking he will say, Behold, I am here. If you remove the bond, and the pointing of the hand, and grumbling speech; 
\v 10 and \add if\add* you give bread to the hungry from your heart, and satisfy the afflicted soul; then your light will spring up in darkness, and your darkness \add will be\add* like noon-day: 
\v 11 and your God will be with you continually, and you will be satisfied as your soul desires; and your bones will be made fat, and will be like a well-watered garden, and like a fountain \add from\add* which the water has not failed. 
\v 12 Your ancient ruins will be rebuilt, and your foundations will last through all generations; and you will be called a builder of walls, and you will put an end to paths that run through the midst. 
\p
\v 13 If you turn away your foot from the sabbath, so as not to do your \f + \fr 58:13 \fqa Gr. \ft pleasures.\f*pleasure on the holy days, and will call the sabbaths delightful, holy to God; \add if\add* you will not lift up your foot to work, nor speak a word in anger out of your mouth, 
\v 14 then you will trust on the Lord; and he will bring you up to the good places of the land, and feed you with the heritage of Jacob your father: for the mouth of the Lord has spoken this. 
\c 59 
\p
\v 1 Has the hand of the Lord no power to save? Or has he made his ear heavy, so that he should not hear? 
\v 2 No, your iniquities separate between you and God, and because of your sins he has turned away \add his\add* face from you, so as not to have mercy \add upon you\add*. 
\v 3 For your hands are defiled with blood, and your fingers with sins; your lips also have spoken wickedness, and your tongue meditates unrighteousness. 
\p
\v 4 No one speaks justly, neither is there true judgment: they trust in vanities, and speak empty \add words\add*; for they conceive trouble, and bring forth wickedness. 
\v 5 They have hatched asps' eggs, and weave a spider's web: and he who is going to eat of their eggs, having crushed an addled egg, has also found a basilisk in it.
\v 6 Their web will not become a garment, nor will they clothe themselves with their works; for their works are works of wickedness. 
\v 7 And \x + \xo 59:7 \xt Rom. 3. 15-17.\x*their feet run to wickedness, swift to shed blood; their thoughts also are thoughts \f + \fr 59:7 \fqa Gr. \ft from murders, but \fqa Alex. \ft reads ὐφρόνων.\f*of murder; destruction and misery are in their ways; 
\v 8 and the way of peace they don't know, neither is there judgment in their ways; for their paths by which they go are crooked, and they don't know peace. 
\p
\v 9 Therefore judgment has departed from them, and righteousness will not overtake them: while they waited for light, darkness came upon them; while they waited for brightness, they walked in perplexity. 
\v 10 They will feel for the wall as blind \add men\add*, and will feel \add for it\add* as if they had no eyes: and they will feel at noon-day as at midnight; they will groan like dying men. 
\v 11 They will proceed together like a bear and like a dove: we have waited for judgment, and there is no salvation, it is gone far from us. 
\p
\v 12 For our wickedness is great before you, and our sins have risen up against us: for our iniquities are in us, and we know our unrighteous deeds. 
\v 13 We have sinned, and dealt falsely, and revolted from our God: we have spoken unrighteous words, and have been disobedient; we have conceived and uttered from our heart unrighteous words. 
\v 14 We have turned judgment back, and righteousness has departed afar off: for truth is consumed in their ways, and they could not pass by a straight \add path\add*. 
\v 15 Truth has been taken away, and they have turned aside \add their\add* mind from understanding. 
\p And the Lord saw it, and it didn't please him that there was no judgment. 
\v 16 He looked, and there was no man, and he observed, and there was none to help: so he defended them with his arm, and established \add them\add* with \add his\add* mercy. 
\v 17 He put on righteousness as a breast-plate, and placed the helmet of salvation on his head; and he clothed himself with the garment of vengeance, and with his cloak, 
\v 18 like one about to give a recompence, \add even\add* reproach to his adversaries. 
\v 19 So those of the west will fear the name of the Lord, and those \add who come\add* from the rising of the sun \add will fear\add* his glorious name: for the wrath of the Lord will come like a mighty river, it will come with fury. 
\p
\v 20 And \x + \xo 59:20 \xt Rom. 11. 26.\x*the deliverer will come for Zion's sake, and will turn away ungodliness from Jacob. 
\v 21 This will be my covenant with them, said the Lord; My Spirit which is upon you, and the words which I have put in your mouth, will never fail from your mouth, nor from the mouth of your seed, for the Lord has spoken it, from now on and forever. 
\c 60 
\p
\v 1 \x + \xo 60:1 \xt Eph. 5. 14.\x*Shine, shine, O Jerusalem, for your light has come, and the glory of the Lord has risen upon you. 
\v 2 Behold, darkness will cover the earth, and \add there will be\add* deep gloom on the nations\f + \fr 60:2 \fqa Gr. \ft darkness and deep gloom will cover the earth on the nations.\f*: but the Lord will appear on you, and his glory will be seen on you. 
\v 3 Kings will walk in your light, and nations in your brightness. 
\p
\v 4 Lift up your eyes around you, and behold your children gathered: all your sons have come from far, and your daughters will be borne on \add men's\add* shoulders. 
\v 5 Then you will see, and fear, and be amazed in your heart; for the wealth of the sea and of nations and peoples will come to you; and herds of camels will come to you, 
\v 6 and the camels of Midian and Gæpha will cover you: all from Saba will come bearing gold, and will bring frankincense, and they will proclaim the salvation of the Lord. 
\v 7 All the flocks of Kedar will be gathered, and the rams of Nabæoth will come; and acceptable sacrifices will be offered on my altar, and my house of prayer will be glorified. 
\p
\v 8 Who are these \add who\add* fly like clouds, and like doves with young ones to me? 
\v 9 The isles have waited for me, and the ships of Tharsis among the first to bring your children from afar, and their silver and their gold with them, for the sake of the holy name of the Lord, and because the Holy One of Israel is glorified. 
\v 10 Strangers will build your walls, and their kings will wait upon you: for because of my wrath I struck you, and because of mercy I loved you. 
\v 11 Your gates will be opened continually; they will not be shut day or night; to bring in to you the power of the nations, and their kings as captives. 
\v 12 For the nations and the kings which will not serve you will perish; and those nations will be made completely desolate. 
\p
\v 13 The glory of Lebanon will come to you, with the cypress, and pine, and cedar together, to glorify my holy place. 
\p
\v 14 The sons of those who afflicted you, and of those who provoked you, will come to you \f + \fr 60:14 \fqa Lit. \ft having feared.\f*in fear; and you will be called Zion, the city of the Holy One of Israel. 
\v 15 Because you have become desolate and hated, and there was no helper, therefore I will make you a perpetual gladness, a joy of many generations. 
\p
\v 16 You will suck the milk of the nations, and will eat the wealth of kings: and will know that I am the Lord who saves you and delivers you, the Holy One of Israel. 
\v 17 For brass I will bring you gold, and for iron I will bring you silver, and instead of wood I will bring you brass, and instead of stones, iron; and I will make your princes peaceable, and your overseers righteous. 
\v 18 Injustice will no more be heard in your land, nor destruction nor misery in your coasts; but your walls will be called Salvation, and your gates Sculptured Work. 
\v 19 \x + \xo 60:19 \xt Rev. 21. 23-27.\x*And you will not have the sun for light by day any more, nor will the rising of the moon lighten your night; but the Lord will be your everlasting light, and God your glory. 
\v 20 For the sun will no more set, nor will the moon be eclipsed; for the Lord will be your everlasting light, and the days of your mourning will be completed. 
\v 21 Your people also will be all righteous; they will inherit the land forever, preserving that which they have planted, \add even\add* the works of their hands, for glory. 
\v 22 The \f + \fr 60:22 \fqa Or, \ft people few in number.\f*little one will become thousands, and the least a great nation; I the Lord will gather them in \add due\add* time. 
\c 61 
\p
\v 1 The Spirit of the Lord is upon me, because he has anointed me; he has sent \x + \xo 61:1 \xt Luke 4. 18.\x*me to preach glad tidings to the poor, to heal the broken in heart, to proclaim liberty to the captives, and recovery of sight to the blind; 
\v 2 to declare the acceptable year of the Lord, and the day of recompence; to comfort all that mourn; 
\v 3 that there should be given to those who mourn in Zion glory instead of ashes, the \f + \fr 61:3 \fqa Alex. \ft reads καταστολὴν as one word.\f*oil of joy to the mourners, \f + \fr 61:3 \fqa Or, \ft anointing.\f*the garment of glory for the spirit of heaviness: and they will be called generations of righteousness, the planting of the Lord for glory. 
\p
\v 4 They will build the old waste places, they will raise up those that were previously made desolate, and will renew the desert cities, \add even\add* those that had been desolate for \add many\add* generations. 
\v 5 Strangers will come and feed your flocks, and aliens \add will be your\add* ploughmen and vine-dressers. 
\v 6 But you will be called priests of the Lord, the ministers of God: you will consume the \f + \fr 61:6 \fqa Gr. \ft strength\f*wealth of nations, and will glory in their wealth. 
\v 7 Thus will they inherit the land a second time, and everlasting joy will be upon their head. 
\v 8 For I am the Lord who loves righteousness and hates robberies of injustice; and I will give their labour to the just, and will make an everlasting covenant with them. 
\v 9 Their seed will be known among the nations, and their offspring among peoples: every one that sees them will \f + \fr 61:9 \fqa Or, \ft acknowledge.\f*take notice of them, that they are a seed blessed by God; 
\v 10 and they will greatly rejoice in the Lord. 
\p Let my soul rejoice in the Lord; for he has clothed me with the robe of salvation, and the garment of joy: he has put a headdress on me like on a bridegroom, and adorned me with ornaments like a bride. 
\p
\v 11 Like the earth bringing forth its flowers, and like a garden its seed; so will the Lord, \add even\add* the Lord, cause righteousness to spring forth, and exultation before all nations. 
\c 62 
\p
\v 1 For Zion's sake I will not hold my peace, and for Jerusalem's sake I will not \f + \fr 62:1 \fqa Gr. \ft relax.\f*rest, until her righteousness goes forth like light, and my salvation burns like a torch. 
\v 2 The nations will see your righteousness, and kings your glory: and one will call you \add by\add* a new name, which the Lord will name. 
\v 3 You will be a crown of beauty in the hand of the Lord, and a royal diadem in the hand of your God. 
\v 4 You will no longer be called Forsaken; and your land will no longer be called Desert: for you will be called My Pleasure, and your land Inhabited: for the Lord has taken pleasure in you, and your land will be inhabited. 
\p
\v 5 As a young man lives with a virgin, so will your sons dwell in \add you\add*: and it will come to pass \add that\add* as a bridegroom will rejoice over a bride, so will the Lord rejoice over you. 
\p
\v 6 On your walls, O Jerusalem, I have set watchmen all day and all night, who will never cease making mention of the Lord. 
\v 7 For there is no one like you, when he has established, and made Jerusalem a praise on the earth. 
\v 8 For the Lord has sworn by his glory, and by the might of his arm, I will no more give your grain and your provisions to your enemies; nor will strangers drink your wine any more, for which you have laboured. 
\v 9 But those who have gathered them will eat them, and they will praise the Lord; and those who have gathered \add the grapes\add* will drink of it in my holy courts. 
\p
\v 10 Go through my gates, and make a way for my people; and cast the stones out of the way; lift up a standard for the nations. 
\v 11 For behold, the Lord has proclaimed to the end of the earth, \x + \xo 62:11 \xt Mat. 21. 5.\x*say to the daughter of Zion, Behold, your Saviour has come to you, having his reward with him and his work before him. 
\v 12 They will call them the holy people, the redeemed of the Lord: and you will be called a city sought out, and not forsaken. 
\c 63 
\p
\v 1 Who is this who has come from Edom, \add with\add* red garments from Bosor? So fair in his clothing, with mighty strength? I \f + \fr 63:1 \fqa Gr. \ft discourse, reason about.\f*speak of righteousness and saving judgment. 
\p
\v 2 Why are your garments red, and your clothing as \add if fresh\add* from a trodden wine-press? 
\v 3 I am full of what has been trampled, and of the nations no one is with me; and I trampled them in my fury, and dashed them to pieces like earth, and brought down their blood to the earth. 
\v 4 For the day of recompence has come upon them, and the year of redemption is at hand. 
\v 5 I looked, and there was no helper; and I observed, and none upheld: therefore my arm delivered them, and my anger drew near. 
\v 6 I trampled them in my anger, and brought down their blood to the earth. 
\p
\v 7 I remembered the mercy of the Lord, the \x + \xo 63:7 \xt 1 Pet. 2. 9.\x*praises of the Lord in all that he has done for us. The Lord is a good judge to the house of Israel; he deals with us according to his mercy, and according to the abundance of his righteousness. 
\p
\v 8 He said, Is it not my people? The children surely will not be rebellious: and he became deliverance to them 
\v 9 out of all their affliction: not an ambassador, nor a messenger, but himself saved them, because he loved them and spared them: he himself redeemed them, and took them up, and lifted them up \f + \fr 63:9 \fqa Gr. \ft all the days of the age.\f*all the days of old. 
\p
\v 10 But they disobeyed, and provoked his Holy Spirit: so he turned to be an enemy, he himself contended against them. 
\v 11 Then he remembered the ancient days, \add saying\add*, Where is he who brought up from the sea the shepherd of the sheep? Where is he who put his Holy Spirit in them? 
\v 12 who led Moses with his right hand, the arm of his glory? He forced the water \add to separate\add* from before him, to make himself an everlasting name. 
\v 13 He led them through the deep, like a horse through the wilderness, and they didn't faint, 
\v 14 and like cattle through a plain: the Spirit came down from the Lord, and guided them: thus you led your people, to make yourself a glorious name. 
\p
\v 15 Turn from heaven, and look from your holy habitation and \add from\add* your glory: where is your zeal and your strength? Where is the abundance of your mercy and of your compassions, that you have withheld yourself from us? 
\v 16 For you are our Father; for \add though\add* Abraham didn't know us, and Israel did not acknowledge us, yet you, O Lord, our Father---deliver us! Your name has been upon us from the beginning. 
\p
\v 17 Why have you let us astray, O Lord, from your way, \add and\add* hardened our hearts, that we should not fear you? Return for your servants' sake, for the sake of the tribes of your inheritance, 
\v 18 that we may inherit your holy mountain for a little while; \f + \fr 63:19 \ft Following differences in Greek MSS, Brenton does not include this last part of verse 18 in the main text, instead including the following footnote: \fqa Heb. \ft and \fqa Alex. \ft + 'our adversaries have trodden down the sanctuary.'\f*our adversaries have trodden down the sanctuary. 
\v 19 We have become as at the beginning, when you did not rule over us, and your name was not called upon us. 
\p
\v 19a \f + \fr 63:19-64:1 \ft Chapter/verse division follows the Hebrew tradition here; traditional LXX versification extends 63:19 and places the break mid-sentence.\f*If only you would open the heaven, the mountains would tremble at your presence and melt,
\c 64 
\nb
\v 1 as wax melts before the fire; and fire will burn up the enemies, and your name will be manifest among the adversaries: at your presence the nations will be troubled, 
\v 2 whenever you work gloriously; trembling from you will take hold upon the mountains. 
\p
\v 3 From of old \x + \xo 64:3 \xt 1 Cor. 2. 9.\x*we have not heard, neither have our eyes seen a God beside you, and your works which you will perform for those who wait for mercy. 
\v 4 For \add these blessings\add* will happen to those who work righteousness, and they will remember your ways: behold, you were angry and we have sinned; therefore we have erred, 
\v 5 and we are all become as unclean, and all our righteousness like a filthy rag: and we have \f + \fr 64:5 \fqa Heb. \ft and \fqa Lit. \ft flowed out.\f*fallen like leaves because of our iniquities; thus the wind will carry us \add away\add*. 
\v 6 There is no one who calls on your name, or who remembers to take hold of you: for you have turned your face away from us, and have delivered us up because of our sins. 
\p
\v 7 Now, O Lord, you are our Father, and we are clay, all \add of us\add* are the work of your hands. 
\v 8 Don't be very angry with us, and don't remember our sins \f + \fr 64:8 \ft The \fqa Gr. \ft ἐν καιρῷ is a \fqa Hebraism.\f*forever; but now look on \add us\add*, for we are all your people. 
\v 9 The city of your holiness has become desolate, Zion has become like a wilderness, Jerusalem a curse. 
\v 10 The house, our sanctuary, and the glory which our fathers blessed, has been burnt with fire: and all our glorious things have gone to ruin. 
\v 11 For all these things you, O Lord, have withheld yourself, and been silent, and have brought us very low. 
\c 65 
\p
\v 1 \x + \xo 65:1 \xt Rom. 10. 20,21.\x*I became visible to those who didn't ask for me; I was found of those who didn't seek me: I said, Behold, I am \add here\add*, to a nation, who didn't call on my name. 
\v 2 I have stretched forth my hands all day to a disobedient and contradicting people, to those who haven't walked in a true way, but after their sins. 
\v 3 This is the people who provoke me continually in my presence; they offer sacrifices in gardens, and burn incense on bricks to devils, which don't exist. 
\v 4 They lie down to sleep in the tombs and in the caves for the sake of dreams, \add even\add* those who eat pig's flesh, and the broth of \add their\add* sacrifices: all their vessels are defiled: 
\v 5 who say, Depart from me, don't draw near to me, for I am pure. 
\p This is the smoke of my anger, a fire burns with it continually. 
\v 6 Behold, it is written before me: I will not be silent until I have repaid into their own lap, 
\v 7 their sins and \add the sins\add* of their fathers, says the Lord, who have burnt incense on the mountains, and reproached me on the hills: I will repay their works into their own lap. 
\p
\v 8 Thus says the Lord, As a grape is found in the cluster, and they say, Don't destroy it; for a blessing is in it: so will I do for the sake of him who serves me, for his sake I will not destroy \add them\add* all. 
\v 9 I will lead forth the seed \add that came\add* of Jacob and of Judah, and they will inherit my holy mountain: and my elect and my servants will inherit it, and will dwell there. 
\v 10 There will be folds of flocks in the forest, and the valley of Achor \add will\add* be for a resting-place of herds for my people, who have sought me. 
\p
\v 11 But you are those who have left me, and forget my holy mountain, and prepare a table for the devil, and fill up the \f + \fr 65:11 \fqa Gr. \ft mixture.\f*drink-offering to Fortune. 
\v 12 I will deliver you up to the sword, you will all fall by slaughter: for I called you, and you didn't listen; I spoke, and you refused to hear; and you did evil in my sight, and chose the things I didn't delight in.
\v 13 Therefore thus says the Lord, Behold, my servants will eat, but you will hunger: behold, my servants will drink, but you will thirst: behold, my servants will rejoice, but you will be ashamed: 
\v 14 behold, my servants will exult with joy, but you will cry for the sorrow of your heart, and will howl for the vexation of your spirit. 
\v 15 For you will leave your name for a loathing to my chosen, and the Lord will destroy you: but my servants will be called by a new name, 
\v 16 which will be blessed on the earth; for they will bless the true God: and those who swear upon the earth will swear by the true God; for they will forget the former affliction, and it will not come into their mind. 
\p
\v 17 For there will be a new heaven and a new earth: and they will surely not remember the former, neither will they come into their mind. 
\v 18 But they will find in her joy and exultation; for, behold, I make Jerusalem a rejoicing, and my people a joy. 
\v 19 I will rejoice in Jerusalem, and will be glad in my people: and never again will there be heard in her the voice of weeping, or the voice of crying. 
\v 20 Neither will there be there any more a \add child who dies\add* untimely, or an old man who will not complete his time: for the youth will be a hundred years \add old\add*, and the sinner who dies at a hundred years will also be accursed: 
\v 21 and they will build houses, and themselves will dwell in \add them\add*; and they will plant vineyards, and themselves will eat the fruit of it. 
\v 22 They will surely not build, and others inhabit; and they will surely not plant, and others eat: for as the days of the tree of life will be the days of my people, they will long enjoy the fruits of their labours. 
\v 23 My chosen will not toil in vain, neither will they father children to be cursed; for they are a seed blessed of God, and their offspring with them. 
\p
\v 24 It will come to pass, \add that\add* before they call, I will listen to them; while they are still speaking, I will say, What is it? 
\v 25 Then wolves and lambs will feed together, and the lion will eat chaff like the ox, and the snake earth as bread. They will not injure nor destroy in my holy mountain, says the Lord. 
\c 66 
\p
\v 1 Thus says the Lord, \x + \xo 66:1 \xt Acts 7. 49,50.\x*Heaven is my throne, and the earth is my footstool: what kind of a house will you build me? And of what kind \add is to be\add* the place of my rest? 
\v 2 For all these things are mine, says the Lord: and to whom will I have respect, but to the humble and meek, and the \add man\add* that trembles \add at\add* my words? 
\p
\v 3 But the transgressor that sacrifices a calf to me, is like he who kills a dog; and he who offers fine flour, like \add one that offers\add* pig's blood; he who gives frankincense for a memorial, is like a blasphemer. 
\p Yet they have chosen their own ways, and their soul has delighted in their abominations. 
\v 4 I also will choose their mockeries, and will recompense their sins upon them; because I called them, and they did not listen to me; I spoke, and they didn't heard: and they did evil before me, and chose the things I didn't delight in.
\p
\v 5 Hear the words of the Lord, you who tremble at his word; say, \f + \fr 66:5 \fqa Alex. \ft ἡμῶν, but \fqa Heb. \ft and \fqa Vat. \ft 'your.'\f*Our brothers, to those who hate and abhor us, Let the name of the Lord be glorified, and let him appear in \f + \fr 66:5 \fqa Or, \ft your.\f*their joy; but they will be ashamed. 
\p
\v 6 A voice of a cry from the city, a voice from the temple, a voice of the Lord repaying \add his\add* adversaries. 
\v 7 Before the one in labour brought forth, before the labour pains come, she suddenly bore a male child.
\v 8 Who has heard such a thing? And who has seen such a thing? Has a land ever been in labour in one day? Or has a nation been born all at once? For Zion was in labour and bore her children. 
\v 9 But I gave this expectation, and you did not remember me, says the Lord: behold, have I not made she who bears and she who is barren? says your God. 
\p
\v 10 Rejoice, O Jerusalem, and all you who love her hold a general assembly in her: rejoice greatly with her, all who \add now\add* mourn over her: 
\v 11 that you may suck, and be satisfied with the breast of her consolation; that you may milk out, and delight yourselves with the influx of her glory. 
\p
\v 12 For thus says the Lord, Behold, I \f + \fr 66:12 \fqa i. e. \ft turn myself.\f*turn toward them like a river of peace, and like a torrent bringing the glory of nations in a flood upon them: their children will be borne upon the shoulders, and comforted on the knees. 
\v 13 As if his mother should comfort one, so will I also comfort you; and you will be comforted in Jerusalem. 
\v 14 You will see, and your heart will rejoice, and your bones will \f + \fr 66:14 \fqa Gr. \ft spring up.\f*thrive like grass: and the hand of the Lord will be known to those who fear him, and he will threaten the disobedient. 
\p
\v 15 For, behold, the Lord will come like fire, and his chariots like a storm, to give his vengeance with wrath, and his rebuke with a flame of fire. 
\v 16 For with the fire of the Lord all the earth will be judged, and all flesh with his sword: many will be killed by the Lord. 
\p
\v 17 Those who sanctify themselves and purify themselves in the gardens, and eat pig's flesh in the porches, and the abominations, and the mouse, will be consumed together, says the Lord. 
\v 18 I \add know\add* their works and their imagination. I am going to gather all nations and tongues; and they will come, and see my glory. 
\v 19 I will leave a sign on them, and I will send forth those who have escaped from them to the nations, to Tharsis, and Phud, and Lud, and Mosoch, and to Thobel, and to Greece, and to the isles afar off, to those who have not heard my name, nor seen my glory; and they will declare my glory among the nations. 
\v 20 They will bring your brothers out of all nations for a gift to the Lord with horses, and chariots, in litters \add drawn by\add* mules with awnings, to the holy city Jerusalem, said the Lord, as though the children of Israel should bring their sacrifices to me with psalms into the house of the Lord. 
\v 21 From them I will take priests and Levites for myself, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 22 For as the new heaven and the new earth, which I make, remain before me, says the Lord, so will your seed and your name continue. 
\v 23 It will come to pass from month to month, and from sabbath to sabbath, \add that\add* all flesh will come to worship before me in Jerusalem, says the Lord. 
\v 24 They will go forth, and see the carcases of the men who have transgressed against me: for their worm will not die, and their fire will not be quenched; and they will be a spectacle to all flesh. 
